WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.480
[Amit Varma]: Quote, video transmissions, cellular phones, fax machines, computer networks.

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:41.160
[Amit Varma]: In the 27 years since then, it would seem that the threats to reading have multiplied

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:42.160
[Amit Varma]: exponentially.

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.800
[Amit Varma]: There is so much competing for our attention, much of it within the endless black mirror

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:48.560
[Amit Varma]: of our smartphones.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:52.120
[Amit Varma]: Physical printed books, in fact, were under threat from e-books, which were supposed to

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:55.440
[Amit Varma]: have made paperbacks and hardcovers entirely redundant.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:59.360
[Amit Varma]: And yes, there are some signs that the world of books and reading has changed massively,

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:03.840
[Amit Varma]: such as the disappearance of bookstores in most of our cities, a matter I cannot stop

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:04.840
[Amit Varma]: lamenting.

00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And yet, it seems that the publishing business worldwide is in pretty good health.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Latest figures showed that printed book sales in the USA have increased year on year for

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:15.480
[Amit Varma]: the last four years.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And publishing in India also seems to be doing pretty well.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:23.480
[Amit Varma]: And I have gotten a small sense of this in the course of the 150 episodes that I have

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.280
[Amit Varma]: recorded of The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, you would have thought that podcasts also would threaten the act of reading, but

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:33.560
[Amit Varma]: over the three years of recording the show, I found that there's a hunger for knowledge

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:38.800
[Amit Varma]: and intelligent discourse out there that is leading people not just to the two hour plus

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:43.320
[Amit Varma]: conversations on this podcast, but also to read more and more books.

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:47.880
[Amit Varma]: I constantly get messages from listeners about how they are reading more because of the books

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I discuss on the show.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:54.880
[Amit Varma]: And that is a matter worth exploring.

00:01:54.880 --> 00:02:00.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:01.240
[Unknown]: science.

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:02.240
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:07.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.040
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is VK Karthikeya, and I hope she won't mind it if I call her one of the

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:14.200
[Amit Varma]: giants of Indian publishing.

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:19.120
[Amit Varma]: She began at Penguin in 1996, left to take charge at HarperCollins a decade later, which

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:21.040
[Amit Varma]: she ran for yet another decade.

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:23.160
[Amit Varma]: And she is now a publisher at Westland.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:28.360
[Amit Varma]: In this time, she's been a player in the evolution of India's publishing industry, and has watched

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.680
[Amit Varma]: not just our reading habits change, but also our society.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.880
[Amit Varma]: I've been trying to put this conversation together for a long time.

