00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:52.840
[Amit Varma]: Karthika, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:52.840 --> 00:03:54.160
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:57.880
[Amit Varma]: Before we get down to the business of books, tell me a little bit about how you happen

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:03.060
[Amit Varma]: to come into publishing to begin with, because it's not like a conventional career choice

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:04.320
[Amit Varma]: that one really has.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:06.520
[Amit Varma]: So how did that happen?

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:11.440
[Guest]: I think like with most people, it happened entirely by accident.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:16.600
[Guest]: I was looking for something to do, you know, how in the what I'm talking about, the late

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:20.480
[Guest]: 80s, early 90s, when I was in university, I was in the University of Hyderabad doing

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:21.680
[Guest]: an MA and MPhil.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.600
[Guest]: Then I came to JNU to do a PhD.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.600
[Amit Varma]: This was all in quest of what to do next.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:27.920
[Amit Varma]: So you're an early anti-national.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.920
[Guest]: I am a total anti-national, past, present, future.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:37.800
[Guest]: And being in JNU was like a brilliant experience, but it showed me nothing of what I could do

00:04:37.800 --> 00:04:43.560
[Guest]: for myself to make a living or to find a vocation or any such thing, because there really wasn't

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:49.160
[Guest]: very much out there for a literature postgraduate who did not want to teach.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:50.720
[Guest]: I did try teaching for a semester.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:52.440
[Guest]: They make you do that when you get a fellowship.

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:54.760
[Guest]: They say go earn your keep.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.200
[Guest]: So you have to do that.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:57.320
[Guest]: And I loved it.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:03.380
[Guest]: But I also did not like the idea of going back to that same space semester after semester.

00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:04.640
[Guest]: I thought it wasn't for me.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:10.120
[Guest]: I have great respect for people who can do that and keep their energy alive and reinvent

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:11.520
[Guest]: themselves every term.

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:14.040
[Guest]: But I didn't think it was for me.

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:17.000
[Guest]: So it was like, you know, am I a journalist?

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.000
[Guest]: Am I going to be?

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
[Guest]: What am I going to be?

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
[Guest]: There was very little television.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.520
[Guest]: My fellow JNUites were just beginning to get into that early television stage.

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:29.920
[Guest]: So Ashutosh, for instance, was in the hostel next door and he was seeing this friend of

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:32.200
[Guest]: mine whom he eventually married.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.880
[Guest]: And everyone was talking about this new Ajtak that was coming up.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:36.640
[Guest]: It was really new.

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:39.380
[Guest]: Everything was fresh and unknown.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:41.840
[Guest]: But I couldn't see myself in that either.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:46.520
[Guest]: So a friend of mine went and did a copyedit test at Penguin.

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:47.880
[Guest]: And he said, I didn't get it.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.800
[Guest]: But you know, you know the language well enough to maybe get in.

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.040
[Guest]: And I thought, hey, that's a luck.

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:55.120
[Guest]: I have to show him I'm better than him maybe.

00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:57.080
[Guest]: And I'll go do this thing.

00:05:57.080 --> 00:05:59.000
[Guest]: And I went off to this office in Nehru Place.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Guest]: I wasn't a Delhi.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.000
[Guest]: I'm not a Delhi person.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.800
[Guest]: I'm like never lived there before I came to JNU.

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:06.160
[Guest]: So anyway, I went looking for it.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:07.640
[Guest]: I went and did a test.

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:10.720
[Guest]: And then they called me back for an interview.

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:13.120
[Guest]: And David Davidar was the publisher then.

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:15.120
[Guest]: So he did an interview as well.

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:18.360
[Guest]: And they said, come and join.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.720
[Guest]: And I had this little wager with myself.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:26.920
[Guest]: I said, if the money they give me is more than what I'm getting as my UGC fellowship,

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:27.920
[Guest]: then I'll take it.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:28.920
[Guest]: Otherwise, obviously not.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:29.920
[Guest]: What's the point?

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:32.240
[Guest]: I don't even know what this job is about.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.680
[Guest]: They offered me 500 rupees more.

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:36.320
[Guest]: And I said, oh, that's not bad.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:38.120
[Guest]: Let me go and do this.

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:39.800
[Guest]: So I went to check it out.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:46.440
[Guest]: And that first week was amazing because it was like falling into the right place without

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.960
[Guest]: any idea that there was even such a place out there.

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:57.000
[Guest]: And by Friday evening, I remember vividly thinking to myself, this is it.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.600
[Guest]: I just want to do this for the rest of my life.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:01.720
[Guest]: And I was darn lucky that that happened.

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:05.280
[Guest]: So that's how I fell into publishing and never left.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:09.720
[Amit Varma]: And I guess one reason why publishing would have seemed such a fit for you was because

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:12.160
[Amit Varma]: I presume you were already someone who loved books.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, tell me a little bit about that.

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:16.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, how did you start reading?

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:20.800
[Amit Varma]: What were the circumstances which allowed you to sort of become an avid reader?

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:22.800
[Amit Varma]: What kind of books did you read?

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Who were the authors you enjoyed reading at that time?

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:27.440
[Guest]: I guess it was my mother.

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:31.960
[Guest]: You know, in Kerala, when you're growing up, there's a lot of reading that happens outside

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:32.960
[Guest]: of comfort zones.

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:36.640
[Guest]: I mean, people read in Malayalam, but they also read in English.

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:41.600
[Guest]: And I remember my mother had these books, she used to go to the H wheeler stand at the

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:44.480
[Guest]: railway station, because that was where their books were.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:48.040
[Guest]: Either you had them in the library, like in the village library or the town library or

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.040
[Guest]: whatever.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:50.240
[Guest]: If you lived in a city, then you had a bigger one.

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:52.760
[Guest]: But you had a lot of libraries in Kerala.

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:55.320
[Guest]: And then you had the H wheeler guys.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:08:02.080
[Guest]: And mom would go to the station and buy those H wheeler stamp two rupee paperbacks to her

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:03.880
[Guest]: two rupees 50 paisa paperbacks.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.920
[Guest]: I still remember seeing those and they're still at home.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:12.200
[Guest]: But they would be random books like there would be Maxim Gorky, a lot of Maxim Gorky

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:16.360
[Guest]: for some reason, there was the usual Agatha Christie and things like that that came up

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:17.360
[Guest]: later.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:21.720
[Guest]: There was a lot of Russian stuff because you remember there were Russian books that were

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:24.660
[Guest]: very popular in India at that time and very cheap.

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:30.080
[Guest]: So there was a lot of reading of literature that came, strangely enough, a lot of it in

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:36.320
[Guest]: translation into English, but read by us as though it was always just English.

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:40.640
[Guest]: And I think I grew up with that cupboard of books, which was my mother's and just read

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:42.680
[Guest]: everything that was in it.

00:08:42.680 --> 00:08:47.360
[Guest]: I also remember reading my first Harold Robbins, which my mother quickly grabbed from me and

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:49.920
[Guest]: said never again, do not read these books.

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:53.320
[Guest]: I was like, if you can read them, why can't I read them?

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:58.000
[Guest]: But those were like really innocent days where you just read what you got and you were satisfied

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.240
[Guest]: with that or you went into the library seeking what you could.

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:06.960
[Guest]: So from there, I also remember that my school in Hyderabad had a large library, which for

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:13.400
[Guest]: some reason, apart from the Russian, the mother, the Quiet Flows the Dawn, like we devoured

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:14.400
[Guest]: those.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:19.280
[Guest]: I cannot imagine a child in school now reading 500 pages of Quiet Flows the Dawn.

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:20.520
[Guest]: There's no reason to, right?

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:23.640
[Guest]: But we had no choice, what was there we read.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:26.920
[Guest]: And I remember discovering Louis L'Amour.

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:27.920
[Guest]: It was fantastic.

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:34.720
[Guest]: I mean, there was this rock star cowboy on a horse going out and conquering the frontiers.

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:39.480
[Guest]: And the strange thing is, when you look back, how little one understood the politics of

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:40.480
[Guest]: it, right?

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:44.360
[Guest]: You read Louis L'Amour and you thought this guy was a hero, this white man on a horse

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:46.760
[Guest]: was just like doing all the right things.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:51.200
[Guest]: And those so-called red Indians were the guys who, well, it's okay for them to go because

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:53.880
[Guest]: they were primitive.

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:58.200
[Guest]: And it's so much later that wisdom dawns and you understand what you were absorbing without

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:06.400
[Guest]: any sense of the world outside of your own little, you know, home and school and library.

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.760
[Guest]: But I think what it did was, it just gave all of us in my generation who are lucky enough

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:18.120
[Guest]: to have those libraries, reading across the world, roaming the world in these ways without

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:19.600
[Guest]: any baggage.

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:20.840
[Guest]: Nobody told us what was right.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:22.160
[Guest]: Nobody told us what was wrong.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:25.760
[Guest]: We had no theory backing us or supporting us.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:30.880
[Guest]: So we just took what we could and we made what we could of it.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:32.600
[Guest]: I'm really grateful I have that.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:36.720
[Guest]: Now when I tell my kids, why aren't you reading this or that or the other, and they have very

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:41.740
[Guest]: solid reasons for why they should do because they have all that armory around them.

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:43.120
[Guest]: We had nothing.

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:49.360
[Guest]: So I guess we were one of the first generations of people who read in English in that way

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:52.440
[Guest]: world literature available to us.

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:55.560
[Guest]: So that's where it began, I guess, my reading.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:11:01.240
[Amit Varma]: No, and I'm just thinking about like, I'm also an 80s kid as partly you are, I guess.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:05.740
[Amit Varma]: And I had JP Narayan, the politician on the show before this, and he was speaking about

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:11.160
[Amit Varma]: growing up in a village in the 60s and then sort of studying in Hyderabad again, like

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:12.840
[Amit Varma]: you did in the 70s.

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:19.040
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that sort of struck me was how a lot of us as individuals and

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:25.480
[Amit Varma]: therefore how society in large is also shaped by the influences we have available to us.

00:11:25.480 --> 00:11:29.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, today, any kid today, your kids, for example, have all the knowledge of the

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:30.760
[Amit Varma]: world available to them.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:33.720
[Amit Varma]: In our times, we didn't really have that.

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you have your typical cultural influences, you have that one TV station,

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Amit Varma]: which is Doordarshan and you have your All India Radio and for those who are lucky enough

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.920
[Amit Varma]: to listen to BBC, and then you have books.

00:11:44.920 --> 00:11:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And even within that world of books, it strikes me that from what I remember is that there

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:56.000
[Amit Varma]: would be a very cliched sort of set of books, which would be standard to the growing up.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.280
[Amit Varma]: Like I'm sure both you and I grew up reading say, Ennett Blyton, of course, you know, Hardy

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:05.080
[Unknown]: Boys and you know, Tintin and Asterix would have been a treat for us.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And how therefore, you know, that becomes almost by happenstance, because there's no

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:12.560
[Amit Varma]: particular reason only those books are available and not so much else.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:17.560
[Amit Varma]: But almost by happenstance, that almost becomes a sort of the bedrock of our thinking.

00:12:17.560 --> 00:12:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's all kind of...

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:24.280
[Guest]: Yeah, in my case, it was I realized also that my father was an educationist, he was the

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:26.240
[Guest]: principal of a school.

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:31.520
[Guest]: And so when I started the first time he actually came and gave me a book to read, which was

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: kind of chosen was Ennett Blyton, because I had chicken pox, I was lying in bed and

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.280
[Guest]: I couldn't do anything and he gave me the famous five.

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:43.000
[Guest]: And I just never wanted to get out of bed after that, because every day I wanted another

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.800
[Guest]: and another and another.

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:49.440
[Guest]: And that kind of discovery of the word that because you're talking about television and

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:52.280
[Guest]: radio, we had like no television at all in those days.

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:58.240
[Guest]: What we did have was radio and mostly for Vinaka Geetamala, and then the cricket commentary.

00:12:58.240 --> 00:13:02.760
[Guest]: So we'd be like glued to the transistor listening to the whatever match was going on anywhere

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:04.160
[Guest]: in the world.

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:07.360
[Guest]: And that was really our only exposure to anything.

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:10.540
[Guest]: Books were all that were there to show us the world.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:15.640
[Guest]: So we were lucky, because if we'd had anything else, I doubt we would have had that same

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:20.600
[Guest]: kind of passion for books as we were able to have because of this.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And given the centrality of books in one's imaginative life for people who were fortunate

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:28.360
[Amit Varma]: enough to sort of be able to access books.

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:29.640
[Amit Varma]: That brings me to my next question.

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:33.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, the rise of Penguin in the 90s and David David of course, is an iconic

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:34.800
[Amit Varma]: figure for many people.

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:39.280
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about what Indian publishing was pre that period pre Penguin

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:40.600
[Amit Varma]: coming in?

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:41.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, how did it function?

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:43.600
[Amit Varma]: Where did who were the publishers who operated?

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:45.520
[Guest]: Where did they get books from?

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:50.480
[Guest]: I think the most of the publishers were very much Indian in that sense.

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:53.080
[Guest]: I mean, certainly Penguin was a big multinational to come in.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:55.020
[Guest]: There was OUP.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:59.360
[Guest]: There was education publishing, but in trade publishing, there were players like J. Coe

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:01.200
[Guest]: and Vickers.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:06.960
[Guest]: And they did publish books and there were a lot of first time publishing that they did,

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:11.720
[Guest]: which then introduced writers who got picked up by other big publishers later.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:12.720
[Guest]: But it was still quite small.

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:17.480
[Guest]: I mean, you had your Malgudi days, and you had bestsellers like that, which were very

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:19.680
[Guest]: much part of the reading circuit.

00:14:19.680 --> 00:14:24.640
[Guest]: By the time Neeraj Choudhury had been published, Raja Rao was being published, there was enough

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:30.320
[Guest]: substantial publishing, but English was still the language that was beginning to be lingua

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:36.560
[Guest]: franca in there were more books being published in the languages than there were in English.

00:14:36.560 --> 00:14:39.760
[Guest]: And this is also the time around the time that Penguin comes in, for instance, something

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:44.840
[Guest]: very beautiful and in the parallel space is happening, which is Kali for Women is coming

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:45.840
[Guest]: up.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:50.640
[Guest]: And that is a completely different sort of the independent press is being set up with

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:52.400
[Guest]: an agenda.

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:56.160
[Guest]: And that press obviously is still around in different way now.

00:14:56.160 --> 00:15:02.760
[Guest]: So while Penguin flourished and decided to follow the Western model, Penguin was modelled

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:07.680
[Guest]: very much on the way, say, Penguin UK would have run or Penguin US would have run.

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:12.720
[Guest]: And all that we see now of the way publishing works in terms of how books are acquired,

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:18.600
[Guest]: how they are marketed and sold, a lot of it owes itself to that time when things were

00:15:18.600 --> 00:15:19.600
[Guest]: set in place.

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:21.600
[Guest]: Now, that could have been done very differently.

00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:26.320
[Guest]: We might have evolved a different way of working if we had looked at the way the independent

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:28.040
[Guest]: presses were functioning.

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:33.620
[Guest]: But these two things came alongside and they both followed completely different trajectories.

00:15:33.620 --> 00:15:37.760
[Guest]: But I think that late 80s is what set the pace.

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:40.120
[Guest]: And it was very, very small.

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:45.360
[Guest]: I remember in the early days in Penguin, we were doing something like 40 books a year.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:48.160
[Guest]: Then it went up to 50, then went up to 60.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:53.440
[Guest]: And that was still a lot of books to try and acquire because of a few people writing.

00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:57.880
[Guest]: There was a lot more work required to get them to be publishable.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:00.120
[Guest]: And there were no computers in the early days.

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:02.040
[Guest]: There was no PDFs to edit with.

00:16:02.040 --> 00:16:03.580
[Guest]: There was all hard copy.

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:07.360
[Guest]: So you would take printouts and then you would mark edits on them.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:09.520
[Guest]: And then the typesetter would put in the corrections.

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:13.600
[Guest]: And I still remember the really interesting way in which covers happened.

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:18.240
[Guest]: So Penguin in those days was an Anand Bazar Patrika joint venture with Penguin UK.

00:16:18.240 --> 00:16:23.760
[Guest]: So the art department was the Anand Bazar art department sitting in Calcutta.

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:28.520
[Guest]: And so a cover would be ideated here, like, you know, this is the book, this is the title,

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:31.880
[Guest]: this is the... and it would be sent to Calcutta.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:35.800
[Guest]: And there would be someone sitting at a desk there who would draw out a cover, and then

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:37.740
[Guest]: courier it back to Delhi.

00:16:37.740 --> 00:16:41.760
[Guest]: And then David would look at it and then do more scrawls and scratches on that.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:44.360
[Guest]: And then it would be couriered back to Calcutta.

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:45.360
[Guest]: And this is how...

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:49.560
[Guest]: I mean, it sounds completely weird now that things could actually function in that way

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:52.040
[Guest]: and be successfully done, but they were done.

00:16:52.040 --> 00:16:58.880
[Guest]: And gradually as computers and emails and all of that happened in the mid 90s, then

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.480
[Guest]: things began to professionalize in a very different way.

00:17:01.480 --> 00:17:07.080
[Guest]: But all along, I mean, as I said, the family owned businesses that were already in India

00:17:07.080 --> 00:17:11.360
[Guest]: and were publishing in English, they were going full tilt at it.

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:15.160
[Guest]: And they were acquiring books, they were editing and publishing.

00:17:15.160 --> 00:17:18.800
[Guest]: Marketing was not so much on the horizon then the way it is.

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:25.360
[Guest]: But a lot of people were invested in distribution, and in bringing books from international markets

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:28.440
[Guest]: in the UK and the US and selling them here.

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:35.120
[Guest]: So it was all very early days, but you can see the foundation of everything we do here

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:40.600
[Guest]: and trace it back to that time, late 80s, mid 80s, maybe is a better time.

00:17:40.600 --> 00:17:44.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, what you just said about the technology that we take for granted brings

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:48.800
[Amit Varma]: to mind is something I was just reading yesterday about an author from a few decades ago complaining

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:51.960
[Amit Varma]: about how you worked for many years on a book and then lost his only manuscript.

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:52.960
[Guest]: Oh, God.

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:56.160
[Amit Varma]: And a young person today may wonder how can there be an only manuscript?

00:17:56.160 --> 00:17:58.200
[Unknown]: Isn't it on the cloud?

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:00.440
[Amit Varma]: What are you talking about?

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:05.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's reflective of the things like another observation a friend of mine had made was

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:11.720
[Amit Varma]: that the generation that is growing up today will never know what it is like to be lost

00:18:11.720 --> 00:18:13.040
[Amit Varma]: because of GPS and all that.

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:17.680
[Guest]: They never actually that sense of physically not knowing where you are, won't exist, which

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:22.800
[Guest]: is almost making up for it by being thoroughly lost in the head half the time.

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:26.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure that's intended for your kids.

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:28.120
[Amit Varma]: If they are listening.

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:32.600
[Amit Varma]: So back then in the late 80s, early 90s, what's the scope of Indian publishing at that point?

00:18:32.600 --> 00:18:35.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, how many books sell?

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:37.720
[Amit Varma]: What is considered a bestseller per se?

00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:42.260
[Amit Varma]: Is it possible to make a living from writing or is it a thing of passion?

00:18:42.260 --> 00:18:47.760
[Guest]: So when I joined, it was 96 year end, I think.

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:53.960
[Guest]: And the books that we were publishing then were printed like 1000 copies, 2000 copies,

00:18:53.960 --> 00:18:54.960
[Guest]: 1500.

00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:58.560
[Guest]: I don't think we ever went over 2000 copies.

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.840
[Guest]: And if we sold 1000 copies, we were quite happy.

00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:03.720
[Guest]: And a lot of books were printed at 1000 copies.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:07.440
[Guest]: I think offset printing required that you did them in certain lots.

00:19:07.440 --> 00:19:12.720
[Guest]: So academic publishing then and even now often does 500 copies of a book.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.520
[Guest]: But Penguin was like trying to reach a larger audience.

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:17.520
[Guest]: It had more commercial ambitions.

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:21.360
[Guest]: So 1000 and 2000 was considered to be the goal.

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:26.200
[Guest]: I think that was roughly how it played out until Arundhati Roy happened.

00:19:26.200 --> 00:19:30.280
[Guest]: And then it was like the sky was just the limit.

00:19:30.280 --> 00:19:35.440
[Guest]: And suddenly you realized that what you thought of as possibly always going to be a small

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:39.520
[Guest]: limited world could conquer the world.

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:45.720
[Guest]: And then the numbers and the print runs, they suddenly became in tens of thousands.

00:19:45.720 --> 00:19:51.120
[Guest]: Of course, even then for a very few titles, but the possibility was there finally.

00:19:51.120 --> 00:19:58.240
[Guest]: And so the irony is that your average book even now is 3000 copies.

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:03.960
[Guest]: So it looks like for 20 years down, we are still looking at almost the same number of

00:20:03.960 --> 00:20:08.960
[Guest]: serious readers in the market who will discover a new book and follow it up and read with

00:20:08.960 --> 00:20:09.960
[Guest]: intent.

00:20:09.960 --> 00:20:17.000
[Guest]: Whereas you have the commercial novels, as they call them, the books that are trending,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.200
[Amit Varma]: being picked up in lakhs.

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:22.200
[Amit Varma]: Would it be fair to say that the long tail is basically the same size?

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:23.200
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:20:23.200 --> 00:20:26.120
[Amit Varma]: But you know, at the bestseller end that has expanded massively.

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:27.120
[Guest]: Truly.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:33.360
[Guest]: That bestseller end has moved in directions we hadn't anticipated at all in those days.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:40.280
[Guest]: I think in those times, it was still the literary novel that seemed to be the only future and

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:43.880
[Guest]: the only kind of star that everybody wanted to reach for.

00:20:43.880 --> 00:20:48.440
[Guest]: It was a complete surprise to people in publishing that actually what people want to read is

00:20:48.440 --> 00:20:53.560
[Guest]: not necessarily the literary novel, which is a formal constructed novel of the West,

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:58.040
[Guest]: but they want something completely different and individualized for home.

00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:02.760
[Guest]: And till that happened, I think we were just like walking in one direction.

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:08.040
[Guest]: And then suddenly it splintered and different possibilities emerged.

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:12.240
[Guest]: Differentiation on the bookshelf emerged, different categories of publishing emerged.

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:17.040
[Guest]: So while everybody was focused on like one kind of thing, either the big narrative nonfiction,

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:21.640
[Guest]: which is the biography of a big figure or like big politics or something apart from

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:28.200
[Guest]: the literary novel, then it suddenly became about commercial novels, about thrillers,

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:34.240
[Guest]: about romance, about spirituality, well being, you know, Mars and Venus kind of books that

00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:36.640
[Guest]: suddenly became the big bestsellers.

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:41.240
[Guest]: So that differentiation, I think, was a sign of maturing of the market and the maturing

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:46.440
[Guest]: of the reader in some way that they had the confidence to choose to read something rather

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:52.000
[Guest]: than just go with what was given to them and almost like a benediction.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:53.240
[Guest]: This is good for you.

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:54.940
[Guest]: These are the books you should read.

00:21:54.940 --> 00:22:00.920
[Guest]: Suddenly became a panic in publishing houses where they said, what happened to the author?

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:03.440
[Guest]: When did the reader become center stage?

00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:07.400
[Guest]: And suddenly when the reader's center stage, then you've got to realign your thinking about

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:10.680
[Guest]: what you want, what the market wants.

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: And you started thinking about the market as a living, breathing thing only then.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.920
[Guest]: All this seems really archaic when you look back, because everything now is geared to

00:22:18.920 --> 00:22:20.120
[Guest]: the market.

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:22.020
[Guest]: Everything is geared to the consumer.

00:22:22.020 --> 00:22:23.920
[Guest]: We didn't use words like consumer then, right?

00:22:23.920 --> 00:22:30.340
[Guest]: We just knew that the person who produces the content is the important person.

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:35.200
[Guest]: That the consumer could be equally important was not on the horizon.

00:22:35.200 --> 00:22:40.320
[Guest]: And now the place where I work at, well, consumer is the word.

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:41.840
[Guest]: It's always about the consumer.

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:43.680
[Guest]: It's about saying, do you know your reader?

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:48.120
[Guest]: How are you giving your reader what they want?

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:51.120
[Guest]: Stop being the person who decides what the reader wants.

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:58.280
[Guest]: So it's a dramatic shift in perception, in the way you work, in the way writing itself

00:22:58.280 --> 00:22:59.680
[Guest]: is happening.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:02.820
[Guest]: Everything is on its head as far as if you looked at it from that point of view.

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:05.760
[Guest]: But it's very straight up for someone who's been born in this time.

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:10.920
[Amit Varma]: No, you know, and for a lot of people focusing on the consumer would almost be infradig.

00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:14.880
[Amit Varma]: It's like, you know, what do they know, and you know, we will be the gatekeepers and the

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:17.080
[Amit Varma]: avatars of good taste.

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:22.600
[Amit Varma]: My other question is sort of related to this that when you get into publishing, obviously,

00:23:22.600 --> 00:23:25.940
[Amit Varma]: when it comes to the heuristics of how do you choose a book or what kind of books you

00:23:25.940 --> 00:23:30.200
[Amit Varma]: look for, I guess your first basic heuristic is obviously your own taste, what you like

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:31.560
[Unknown]: and what you don't like.

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:35.000
[Amit Varma]: But then you have to go beyond this very fast when you start thinking of the market.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's especially so in a marketplace that expands as rapidly like shortly after

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:45.600
[Guest]: you come on the scene, then Arundhati's book happens and Chetan Bhagat happens in the early

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:46.600
[Guest]: 2000s.

00:23:46.600 --> 00:23:49.520
[Amit Varma]: And people are just reading different kinds of things.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:50.680
[Amit Varma]: What is this process like?

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing that I often speak about to fellow editors, which is in journalism, of

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:59.720
[Amit Varma]: course, not publishing, but to fellow editors and to people who commission podcasts and

00:23:59.720 --> 00:24:04.280
[Amit Varma]: whatever people who are in that editorial filtering decision making process, is that

00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:07.120
[Amit Varma]: the most important quality you must have is humility.

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:12.920
[Amit Varma]: And assume that your own tastes are necessarily determine what is good or what is bad or what

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:14.880
[Amit Varma]: people want or what people don't want.

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:18.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, people are very diverse, they want all kinds of things.

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:22.400
[Amit Varma]: So you've got to sort of have the humility to step back from your own preferences and

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:25.900
[Amit Varma]: biases and be sort of open to that.

00:24:25.900 --> 00:24:29.760
[Amit Varma]: How was that process for you of developing your vision as an editor?

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:33.560
[Guest]: I think publishing is the most paradoxical space in many ways.

00:24:33.560 --> 00:24:39.640
[Guest]: It's like different forces pulling against each other in almost everything you do.

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:44.280
[Guest]: And part of that, I think, is this thing of choosing what you want to publish.

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest]: On the one hand, yes, what you want to read is what you want to publish.

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:55.320
[Guest]: And I would never underestimate that, because in many ways, the reader and the editor are,

00:24:55.320 --> 00:25:01.480
[Guest]: especially if you speak about it in situations of say class and location of geography, etc.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:05.200
[Guest]: In a certain way, you'll find that there are very similar people.

00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:11.360
[Guest]: And maybe what you think is a strong book would resonate with those many people for

00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:12.640
[Guest]: sure.

00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:20.640
[Guest]: So the trick, I think, is to decide the identity of that reader and to say, OK, this is one

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.320
[Guest]: book that I think is wonderful.

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:25.640
[Guest]: And I'm sure there are like a few thousand people out there who read it.

00:25:25.640 --> 00:25:30.480
[Guest]: But there might be another book which I may not read or pick up for myself.

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:34.200
[Guest]: But maybe there are 100,000 readers out there who will read that.

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:40.000
[Guest]: What we would try and do is to find a reader in-house whose taste might resonate with those

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.680
[Guest]: 100,000 people as well.

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:48.880
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think diversity within a publishing house is the one big thing, because

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:54.880
[Guest]: you cannot have it as one taste across all editors, all bringing in the same kind of

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:55.880
[Guest]: thing.

00:25:55.880 --> 00:26:01.280
[Guest]: So as long as there are different minds at work and different tastes at work, we will

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:04.600
[Guest]: always be able to reach different kinds of readers.

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:10.120
[Guest]: And the humility you speak of, I think part of that humility is to say, you may be the

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:13.080
[Guest]: publisher, you may be one of the senior people, none of that matters.

00:26:13.080 --> 00:26:17.840
[Guest]: If there's someone who's on her in her first month in publishing, who falls in love with

00:26:17.840 --> 00:26:23.320
[Guest]: the book, one has to also listen to that and say, OK, we don't know this.

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:27.480
[Guest]: But clearly, if this person loves it, then there must be something to it.

00:26:27.480 --> 00:26:30.720
[Guest]: And we need to follow that instinct as well.

00:26:30.720 --> 00:26:35.920
[Guest]: So not being set in one way or deciding for everyone.

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:41.600
[Guest]: I think that's the first step that all of us learn in that journey of how to and what

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:42.600
[Amit Varma]: to publish.

00:26:42.600 --> 00:26:47.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the most like I came across this awesome study a few years ago when I

00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:52.720
[Amit Varma]: read Philip Tetlock's book, Super Forecasting, where he talks about how the most important

00:26:52.720 --> 00:26:58.160
[Amit Varma]: factor for good decision making in any company is not intelligence or education or any of

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:00.960
[Amit Varma]: those things you might normally assume, but diversity.

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:03.680
[Amit Varma]: That's the most important sort of determinant.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:08.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it is in every company's self interest to sort of enhance the diversity

00:27:08.080 --> 00:27:12.040
[Guest]: of the workplace, not for its own sake, but just in terms of business, it makes business

00:27:12.040 --> 00:27:13.040
[Guest]: sense.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:14.840
[Amit Varma]: You have and what you said, obviously speaks to that.

00:27:14.840 --> 00:27:19.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, one criticism a lot of people do have of publishing even today is that it's

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:21.440
[Amit Varma]: not diverse enough that you find.

00:27:21.440 --> 00:27:23.200
[Amit Varma]: I agree, it's kind of homogenous.

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:24.640
[Guest]: I agree entirely.

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:29.720
[Guest]: It's partly the language we work with the sophisticated narrative, which is what we

00:27:29.720 --> 00:27:36.280
[Guest]: expect to publish when we hire editors, as though you're hiring them at the level of

00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:42.840
[Guest]: literary fiction editors, when actually you might want people who are editing Sri Sri

00:27:42.840 --> 00:27:46.840
[Guest]: Ravi Shankar, or, you know, something like that.

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:51.960
[Guest]: So now I think all of us are learning that that differentiation is very, very important.

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:57.600
[Guest]: And you have to have people who think differently, and who read differently, and who use language

00:27:57.600 --> 00:27:58.600
[Guest]: differently.

00:27:58.600 --> 00:28:01.960
[Guest]: There's no point in I often think there's that there's no point in my going out to try

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:07.920
[Guest]: and commission a book that a 17 year old might, you know, completely take to if I'm really

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:08.920
[Guest]: skilled at my job.

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:12.640
[Guest]: And if I've really read enough, and I'm able to put myself into the heads of all kinds

00:28:12.640 --> 00:28:15.360
[Guest]: of people, I just might be able to.

00:28:15.360 --> 00:28:17.000
[Guest]: But I think that's really difficult.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:20.960
[Guest]: I think you need to have specialists in every category.

00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:25.680
[Guest]: You need to have people who develop not only their instinct for that category, but also

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:30.880
[Guest]: experience in that category, who can deepen their understanding of the subject while casting

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:34.880
[Guest]: around to see what is the broadest base of readership and commission to that there's

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:35.880
[Guest]: a lot more science.

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:38.920
[Guest]: I mean, I always used to think publishing was all about art.

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:46.280
[Guest]: You know, it was like the final thing to do, getting the politics, the nuance, the writing,

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:49.440
[Guest]: that's all there still, I don't think it's devoid of that.

00:28:49.440 --> 00:28:54.320
[Guest]: But I think that art without the science, the art without the algorithm in today's world

00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:56.040
[Guest]: is not going to be effective.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:29:02.320
[Amit Varma]: No, and while I entirely sort of agree with the shift towards keeping the consumer at

00:29:02.320 --> 00:29:07.360
[Amit Varma]: the centre, which I would say is essentially an overdue respect for readers and what they

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:09.920
[Amit Varma]: want, are there values that go beyond that?

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:14.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, if I may use an analogy, it just strikes me thinking aloud that the editor

00:29:14.120 --> 00:29:18.320
[Amit Varma]: of a publishing house is somewhat like a zookeeper and you're running a zoo and you've got all

00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:19.720
[Amit Varma]: kinds of animals.

00:29:19.720 --> 00:29:23.240
[Amit Varma]: But after a period of time, you realise that everyone wants to see the lion and the elephant

00:29:23.240 --> 00:29:24.880
[Amit Varma]: and the hyena and whatever.

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:29.160
[Amit Varma]: And there are certain exotic or even mundane species, perhaps which nobody wants to see.

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:32.640
[Amit Varma]: So they don't, you know, they're just taking a valuable real estate, they're not worth

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:33.640
[Amit Varma]: the money.

00:29:33.640 --> 00:29:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And then the zookeeper has a choice that you know, does he keep them there?

00:29:37.440 --> 00:29:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Or does he remove them?

00:29:38.840 --> 00:29:43.320
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, are they sort of a higher set of values where you say that, okay, for example,

00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:48.600
[Amit Varma]: poetry may not sell, but I will nevertheless subsidise my poetry imprint with, you know,

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:53.280
[Amit Varma]: the revenues I get from selling bestsellers elsewhere, because it is important for us

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:55.120
[Amit Varma]: to do as publishers.

00:29:55.120 --> 00:29:59.520
[Amit Varma]: And this, in a sense, is a larger question that also correlates with a similar question

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:03.640
[Amit Varma]: you could ask about journalism that are you going to be entirely market driven, or are

00:30:03.640 --> 00:30:05.760
[Amit Varma]: there some kind of higher values?

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And to follow up on that, if there are higher values that go beyond the logic of the market,

00:30:10.440 --> 00:30:15.400
[Amit Varma]: are they inherent in the logic of the profession that is either journalism or publishing in

00:30:15.400 --> 00:30:20.600
[Amit Varma]: your case, or will they necessarily come from the individuals who happen to be there?

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:23.480
[Guest]: So many things to think about here.

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:27.800
[Guest]: I don't know if anything is beyond the logic of the market, because what you're seeing,

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:32.320
[Guest]: the fewer numbers, the failure, perhaps of some things is also the logic of the market

00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:35.000
[Guest]: that's driving it to non existence.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:39.440
[Guest]: And I think there is a call to be taken, for instance, literary fiction, more than poetry

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:41.280
[Guest]: in some ways.

00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:49.680
[Guest]: Literary fiction is always going to be a difficult thing to publish, I think, because it is premised

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:54.840
[Guest]: on the assumption that there are readers out there who are willing to invest a certain

00:30:54.840 --> 00:31:00.440
[Guest]: kind of time and intelligence, and also effort in reading, right?

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:05.960
[Guest]: And who feel that there is a value attached to that work, which they are willing to explore

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:07.720
[Guest]: and imbibe.

00:31:07.720 --> 00:31:13.000
[Guest]: And as long as that continues to be a difficult space, there will always be the temptation

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:19.240
[Guest]: to say, why do it, you know, you can do five books in that space, it requires less effort,

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:21.920
[Guest]: and you will still make much more money.

00:31:21.920 --> 00:31:25.400
[Guest]: But I think that is non negotiable, as far as I'm concerned.

00:31:25.400 --> 00:31:33.160
[Guest]: Part of why publishing continues to be important is because it produces ideas, it produces

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:41.560
[Guest]: a way forward for thinking about language, about construction of thought of society of

00:31:41.560 --> 00:31:44.320
[Guest]: the way we live and the way we dream.

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:48.600
[Guest]: These are not things that you can put away at any cost.

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:54.040
[Guest]: They need to be there, they need to be supported, they need to be put out in the world for people

00:31:54.040 --> 00:31:56.160
[Guest]: to receive or not receive.

00:31:56.160 --> 00:32:01.200
[Guest]: And the interesting thing about publishing in India is that your stakes are not that

00:32:01.200 --> 00:32:04.720
[Guest]: high in individual books in terms of your investment, either, you're not going to go

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:10.240
[Guest]: under, because you backed one literary novel, it would go under if your entire list was

00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:16.000
[Guest]: literary fiction, and they weren't all of the kind of I mean, like one of the acquisitions,

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:17.880
[Guest]: of course, that too much is getting published, right?

00:32:17.880 --> 00:32:22.000
[Guest]: So that I would agree with that there's no point in putting on books that perhaps somebody

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:27.080
[Guest]: else could do, or maybe they could just go out into that whole self published space.

00:32:27.080 --> 00:32:30.480
[Guest]: Maybe you don't need a mainstream publisher for that.

00:32:30.480 --> 00:32:38.520
[Guest]: But otherwise, being selective, putting out the best of writing that is available to you.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:44.600
[Guest]: That is, I hesitate to use the word duty, because it isn't like the right word in a

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:47.880
[Guest]: place where we talk about markets and consumerism.

00:32:47.880 --> 00:32:53.840
[Guest]: But I think publishing is still old world enough to nurture that sense of duty and responsibility

00:32:53.840 --> 00:33:01.160
[Guest]: and to say, what are you as a publisher, if your job is merely to make money, then I don't

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:05.440
[Guest]: think publishing supports that worldview yet.

00:33:05.440 --> 00:33:09.840
[Guest]: There are publishers and there are spaces within publishing that do but from where I'm

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:16.080
[Guest]: sitting, I'm seeing it as a job that has a responsibility of putting books into the world

00:33:16.080 --> 00:33:21.440
[Guest]: that aid a conversation that aid discourse that aid intelligent thinking about the way

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:22.840
[Guest]: we live.

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:26.640
[Guest]: And it could be nonfiction, it could be fiction, it could be poetry, any of these things, the

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:30.760
[Guest]: challenge and the other side of that duty and responsibility is to make sure that my

00:33:30.760 --> 00:33:35.640
[Guest]: company doesn't suffer for that, that the way I publish these books, the way I bring

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:40.720
[Guest]: in the right books, the way we package them, the way we sell and market and tell the world

00:33:40.720 --> 00:33:45.000
[Guest]: why they need to be read, that needs to be done in such a way that you will find the

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:49.880
[Guest]: readers for them, and that they will go on to maybe get an award or go on shortlists

00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:53.760
[Guest]: or whatever it is that takes to get some more visibility for them, and gives the author

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:57.640
[Guest]: the satisfaction that her words are being read and appreciated in the way they were

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:58.940
[Guest]: meant to be.

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:03.580
[Guest]: So it's a double edged thing, you need to do it, but you also need to do it smartly.

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:07.880
[Guest]: And to make sure that you don't you don't publish a book that then goes nowhere or just

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:08.880
[Guest]: sinks.

00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:10.380
[Guest]: That's no good for anyone.

00:34:10.380 --> 00:34:15.560
[Guest]: So it's a daily challenge to put the good book out there and get it to sell.

00:34:15.560 --> 00:34:20.120
[Guest]: But even if you don't sell it all, even if you just break even, I still think it's something

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:22.440
[Guest]: that we have a responsibility to do.

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:24.440
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of the economics of it.

00:34:24.440 --> 00:34:28.100
[Amit Varma]: Like when you talk about how the stakes are not too high, and by backing one literary

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:30.680
[Amit Varma]: author, we won't necessarily go broke.

00:34:30.680 --> 00:34:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, even if we break even, it's something we're doing, what is sort of break

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:37.720
[Amit Varma]: even like how many copies does a book need to sell for it?

00:34:37.720 --> 00:34:38.720
[Guest]: Right.

00:34:38.720 --> 00:34:44.040
[Guest]: So if I've taken on a novel that I think I would have to sell something like 5000 copies

00:34:44.040 --> 00:34:50.800
[Guest]: to earn out, say the advance for the author, and if I end up selling 2500 copies, I will

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:55.440
[Guest]: be writing off a certain amount of money that should be earned out by the advance and is

00:34:55.440 --> 00:34:57.320
[Guest]: not being earned out.

00:34:57.320 --> 00:35:01.760
[Guest]: But I would have broken even in the sense that overall, I may not have made the usual

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:08.400
[Guest]: 7 to 10% margin, which is all publishing margins are, I may end up with zero, nothing gained,

00:35:08.400 --> 00:35:09.840
[Guest]: nothing lost.

00:35:09.840 --> 00:35:15.480
[Guest]: But as long as the advance has been reasonable, and premised on that first print run, we're

00:35:15.480 --> 00:35:19.600
[Guest]: okay if you sell roughly 60% of that print run.

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And do you find other publishers also, you know, share this sort of sense of you didn't

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:25.800
[Amit Varma]: want to use the word duty.

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:31.480
[Amit Varma]: So this sense of duty in a sense, it's not a bad word, towards keeping literature, poetry,

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:35.560
[Amit Varma]: all of these genres sort of alive in some way or the other while one goes about the

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:37.080
[Amit Varma]: business of selling books.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:41.320
[Guest]: I think a lot of them do the conversations I have with my colleagues and other publishing

00:35:41.320 --> 00:35:46.880
[Guest]: houses is often how to do this balancing act, how do we sell books?

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:52.040
[Guest]: But how do we also do books that we really deeply care about and feel should be published?

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:57.200
[Guest]: It's a battle that everyone is fighting, and I know very few people who don't care about

00:35:57.200 --> 00:35:58.200
[Guest]: it.

00:35:58.200 --> 00:36:01.760
[Guest]: There are some who've taken the conscious decision that okay, somebody else in house

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:03.440
[Guest]: is doing that part of the job.

00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:07.060
[Guest]: My job is to bring in the revenue in a certain way, and I will do that.

00:36:07.060 --> 00:36:13.400
[Guest]: But I think even in doing that, they contribute to that larger idea that publishing still

00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:17.080
[Guest]: has a job to do that is beyond revenue.

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:22.320
[Guest]: And for as long as we can keep that as center stage, I think we'll all be the beneficiaries

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:23.400
[Guest]: of it.

00:36:23.400 --> 00:36:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And how have your sort of own reading taste evolved, you know, over this entire journey?

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:32.520
[Amit Varma]: Because you obviously start off with a set of preferences, but then you have to widen

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:37.720
[Amit Varma]: your reading as a matter of professional duty, you just have to pretty much read everything.

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:39.160
[Guest]: And how does that evolve?

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:41.100
[Guest]: I think I started out by reading everything.

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:45.720
[Guest]: So that was probably the best thing I did for myself as an editor unknowingly.

00:36:45.720 --> 00:36:48.240
[Guest]: I never felt a sense of hierarchy in my reading.

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:53.800
[Guest]: Nobody ever told me and I didn't feel that reading Enid Blyton was less than reading

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:54.920
[Guest]: Gorky or whatever.

00:36:54.920 --> 00:36:57.080
[Guest]: I didn't know the difference.

00:36:57.080 --> 00:37:03.880
[Guest]: But I think a lot of my understanding of publishing and the kinds of books I want to do come from

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:08.800
[Guest]: my years in university, especially Central University in Hyderabad.

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:15.440
[Guest]: We had a fantastic set of teachers who, through literary theory at us, you can imagine someone

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:20.120
[Guest]: coming out of an undergraduate course in a conventional college comes to a university

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:24.440
[Guest]: where the faculty is like, just come back from doing PhDs in literary theory in the

00:37:24.440 --> 00:37:25.440
[Guest]: US.

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:27.640
[Guest]: And they come and tell you the author's dead.

00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:31.160
[Guest]: And I mean, even that notion that the author's dead actually is like from 10 years ago, you

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:33.200
[Guest]: guys just discovering it now.

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:38.600
[Guest]: We'd never come up with words like feminism in such a way as in that space.

00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:42.440
[Guest]: And you suddenly discover that it's not just pleasure that you're reading for, but that

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:46.960
[Guest]: there are processes that go into reading and analyzing that pleasure that allow you to

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:52.400
[Guest]: then understand how to construct a book differently and to make that pleasure possible for someone

00:37:52.400 --> 00:37:53.400
[Guest]: else.

00:37:53.400 --> 00:37:57.520
[Guest]: This seems like something that wasn't intended at all by my teachers.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:01.840
[Guest]: They thought they were teaching us for, you know, to make educators of us.

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:07.800
[Guest]: But as I got into publishing, and as I started working on books, I think all of these theoretical

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:13.720
[Guest]: understandings and political understandings of the text of trying to struggle with a Derrida

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:20.040
[Guest]: or a Spivak or reading Canadian writers and American and Australian writers and trying

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:23.660
[Guest]: to understand how they use language so differently.

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:28.200
[Guest]: It knocks everything out of you, any learning that you thought was to be taken seriously.

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:32.800
[Guest]: All you know is that it's a blank slate every time you open a book and what you get could

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:35.520
[Guest]: surprise you or could disappoint you.

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:39.320
[Guest]: But every single work is an experience in itself.

00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:43.400
[Guest]: And I think if you can open a book, every manuscript that comes to you in that same

00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:47.960
[Guest]: way and say, I don't know what to expect from this, but whatever it is, let me read it in

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:49.200
[Guest]: its own terms.

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:55.320
[Guest]: Let me read it as what it sets out to be, not what I would like to read or what I would

00:38:55.320 --> 00:38:56.920
[Guest]: like to see.

00:38:56.920 --> 00:39:01.200
[Guest]: Then I think you're already better off in your editorial approach.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:07.120
[Guest]: I mean, you will go to it with a more open mind than if you had standards of excellence

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:11.320
[Guest]: that had to be met in a certain way and only in that way.

00:39:11.320 --> 00:39:17.200
[Guest]: So what I'm trying to say is that the reading that I did expanded into reading about writing

00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:19.120
[Guest]: and reading about reading.

00:39:19.120 --> 00:39:20.640
[Guest]: And there was a lot of poetry in that.

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:22.800
[Guest]: And I had extraordinary teachers.

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:28.840
[Guest]: My supervisor was a Maharashtrian who read Kipling with great enthusiasm and showed me

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:30.680
[Guest]: how to read historical fiction in a certain way.

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:35.120
[Guest]: I did my MPhil on Mary Renaud, this wonderful historical fiction writer who's got this fabulous

00:39:35.120 --> 00:39:37.760
[Guest]: series on Alexander.

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:39.920
[Guest]: And so I worked on that.

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:44.040
[Guest]: And now when I edit historical fiction, I'm grateful I had that.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:47.240
[Guest]: I had Hoshang Merchant as my professor.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:53.360
[Guest]: He read American poetry to us and talked about gender in a way that was very distant from

00:39:53.360 --> 00:39:58.260
[Guest]: Tejaswini Niranjana, who was my introduction to feminist reading, who does a completely

00:39:58.260 --> 00:40:01.120
[Guest]: different reading of gender than him.

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:04.880
[Guest]: You know, so when you get thrown into a space like that, where people are coming at you

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:09.720
[Guest]: with ideas that are so different, each of them has a position and each of them fairly

00:40:09.720 --> 00:40:12.400
[Guest]: fierce in their positions.

00:40:12.400 --> 00:40:18.440
[Guest]: You just can't approach a text either neutrally or objectively, as they say.

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:21.960
[Guest]: You have to fight with it a little bit like you struggle with it.

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:24.720
[Guest]: You dig deeper if you can.

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:29.680
[Guest]: And so as it happens, I think the very first book I commissioned as an editor at Penguin

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:33.440
[Guest]: was a collection of queer writing edited by Hoshang.

00:40:33.440 --> 00:40:37.740
[Guest]: And that was an eye opener in itself, the kind of text that came in the way we worked

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:38.740
[Guest]: on it.

00:40:38.740 --> 00:40:43.820
[Guest]: And I think one of my dearest memories from that time of surprise in publishing and writers

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:48.800
[Guest]: was God, David had said, yes, go ahead and commission this book.

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:52.000
[Guest]: And Hoshang had given me a list of his like wish list.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:53.000
[Guest]: And I was adding to that.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.320
[Guest]: And then we were writing off letters to people.

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:58.160
[Guest]: And I remember we were sitting in this little conference room we had where all the commissioning

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:00.800
[Guest]: editors were sitting, there were five of us with David.

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:03.680
[Guest]: And suddenly there was this call, we had landlines only.

00:41:03.680 --> 00:41:06.960
[Guest]: And somebody was calling from the reception to say there's someone for me.

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:07.960
[Guest]: And I was like, who is it?

00:41:07.960 --> 00:41:08.960
[Guest]: And they said, Vikram Seth.

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:13.480
[Guest]: And I was like, Vikram Seth was talking to me?

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:17.720
[Guest]: And I remember being really nervous and shaky about even taking this call.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:22.840
[Guest]: And he was calling to say, I got your letter about inclusion in this anthology you're doing.

00:41:22.840 --> 00:41:24.200
[Guest]: And I'm very happy to be in it.

00:41:24.200 --> 00:41:27.640
[Guest]: I just thought I'd write I'd call and tell you myself.

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:32.560
[Guest]: I was floored, you know, that he thought it was important enough to do this.

00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:33.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm floored listening to this.

00:41:33.880 --> 00:41:38.360
[Guest]: I mean, I was like this young editor on my first commissioned, you know, book.

00:41:38.360 --> 00:41:41.240
[Guest]: So it just, it is an amazing world.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:46.800
[Guest]: Every day you come up on people who surprise you, who make you think about all the good,

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:49.000
[Guest]: best things in life.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:53.520
[Guest]: And each time something lets you down, you find two other people or two other situations

00:41:53.520 --> 00:41:57.640
[Guest]: that quickly bolster you and say, no, no, no, all is good.

00:41:57.640 --> 00:41:58.840
[Guest]: It's better.

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:03.860
[Guest]: And I think that is the best thing about being in publishing these people around you, whose

00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:10.960
[Guest]: books you read and work with, sometimes you don't work with ever, but they enrich your

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:11.960
[Guest]: environment.

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:16.600
[Amit Varma]: So you were speaking about, you know, learning how to read, for example, and a few days back,

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:20.920
[Amit Varma]: I reread Harold Bloom's book on learning how to read and why I think it's called and whenever

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:24.600
[Amit Varma]: people for example, tell me that they can't understand poetry, for example, though they

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:28.880
[Amit Varma]: are otherwise readers, I give them a copy of Mary Oliver's poetry handbook, because

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:29.880
[Guest]: that's such a lovely book.

00:42:29.880 --> 00:42:31.920
[Guest]: And it really helps you appreciate poetry.

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:36.840
[Guest]: Today somebody posted a tweet, a poem from that the bride and the bridegroom.

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:38.120
[Guest]: What was that?

00:42:38.120 --> 00:42:43.280
[Guest]: The bridegroom embracing the world and the bride embracing embrace amazement.

00:42:43.280 --> 00:42:44.280
[Amit Varma]: Something like that.

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:45.280
[Guest]: It was beautiful lines.

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:46.280
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:42:46.280 --> 00:42:47.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's again, a heck of a book.

00:42:47.480 --> 00:42:53.000
[Amit Varma]: So just asking you about like one, obviously, the nature of how you read a book changes

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.400
[Amit Varma]: as you elaborated upon when you are an editor, when you're a publisher changes completely,

00:42:57.400 --> 00:42:59.920
[Amit Varma]: you just you know, you find different depths.

00:42:59.920 --> 00:43:04.440
[Amit Varma]: But if you had to, for example, advise my listeners, who might be earnest readers, you

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:09.200
[Amit Varma]: know, on the subject of what should they read to enhance the way they read?

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:10.680
[Guest]: What are the recommendations you'd have?

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:16.760
[Guest]: You know, I don't think there are any particular texts that can help you read.

00:43:16.760 --> 00:43:19.640
[Guest]: Reading is its own learning.

00:43:19.640 --> 00:43:24.280
[Guest]: The more you read the many kinds of texts you read analysis of it would help if you

00:43:24.280 --> 00:43:27.440
[Guest]: are in the frame of mind to be receptive to that.

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:33.360
[Guest]: But otherwise, just exploring texts and as many kinds of texts as you can reading poetry

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:40.280
[Guest]: today reading a novel tomorrow reading a graphic novel the day after reading narrative nonfiction.

00:43:40.280 --> 00:43:43.960
[Guest]: The good thing about our digital experience now is that you can Google and say what are

00:43:43.960 --> 00:43:45.960
[Guest]: the 10 best books in each category.

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:50.400
[Guest]: And it's interesting that there are many cliches in there, but there's usually very, very good

00:43:50.400 --> 00:43:52.040
[Guest]: recommendations in there.

00:43:52.040 --> 00:43:56.040
[Guest]: So you can find practically any kind of book you're in the mood for.

00:43:56.040 --> 00:43:59.440
[Guest]: And I don't think there's any substitute for that reading.

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:04.080
[Guest]: There are few books that can tell you how to read as well as the books themselves can

00:44:04.080 --> 00:44:06.120
[Guest]: tell you.

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:16.520
[Guest]: And I also think that poetry is an invaluable guide to how to read because it and to write

00:44:16.520 --> 00:44:24.200
[Guest]: because it's almost like a laboratory where you're shaking up the words and reconfiguring

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:30.880
[Guest]: them, throwing in something different, something new, a comma in one place and not the other

00:44:30.880 --> 00:44:34.280
[Guest]: can change the way you breathe that line.

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:38.320
[Guest]: And that changes the way you write or read that line.

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:43.080
[Guest]: And things like that only come to you when you as you keep reading, like nobody will

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:47.080
[Guest]: be able to point that out to you in the way that you can point it out to yourself if you

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:48.160
[Guest]: get it.

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:53.800
[Guest]: But if you had to read a book on say grammar, you know, like you read leaves shoots,

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Eat shoots leaves, right?

00:44:54.800 --> 00:44:55.800
[Amit Varma]: Which itself contains many errors.

00:44:55.800 --> 00:45:01.400
[Guest]: But you read that kind of book and you say, hey, this is fun.

00:45:01.400 --> 00:45:03.640
[Unknown]: This isn't like all hard work, right?

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:08.320
[Guest]: But then you read one essay like the death of the author by Roland Barthes, and you have

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: to rethink the way you thought about reading altogether.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:18.740
[Guest]: And I think that essay for me was like a changing point, a turning point where all the old ideas

00:45:18.740 --> 00:45:23.120
[Guest]: go out to the window, and then you realize that you need to find a different way to read

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:24.800
[Guest]: altogether.

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:30.200
[Guest]: To me, one of the biggest educations in how to read is crime writing.

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:34.040
[Guest]: Because when you read a crime novel, which is really well written, I'm talking about

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:39.600
[Guest]: the near literary crime fiction, which so much of it actually exists, you can almost

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:43.920
[Guest]: unpack the way the structure works, right?

00:45:43.920 --> 00:45:50.200
[Guest]: You can see where the red herrings were, because you will remember them, you will see how language

00:45:50.200 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: shifts in terms of description, atmosphere, to the crispness of dialogue, to light and

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:02.400
[Guest]: sound and shape, all the things that go into making something of complete experience, it's

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:05.340
[Guest]: all there in crime fiction, in the best of crime fiction.

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:10.320
[Guest]: And when you read that, in a way, it's like reading poetry, because a lot of it is also

00:46:10.320 --> 00:46:15.440
[Guest]: about exploring other worlds, other countries, other cultures.

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:19.720
[Guest]: So much of your understanding of culture can come from crime fiction, which is very close

00:46:19.720 --> 00:46:23.920
[Guest]: to the ground in those places and looks at the underbelly of things and the governance

00:46:23.920 --> 00:46:32.040
[Guest]: and all of that, that I think you arrive at an understanding of how text works.

00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:36.920
[Guest]: And even if you're not a crime fiction fan, I think if you're a reader, and if you're

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:43.000
[Guest]: an editor, I think it's great learning more than reading a book about how to read or write.

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:47.040
[Amit Varma]: No, and I absolutely agree with you, especially about poetry, just looking, I think poetry,

00:46:47.040 --> 00:46:51.520
[Amit Varma]: if you're reading carefully forces you to look at language with a granularity that then

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:55.520
[Amit Varma]: enhances your understanding of it and your use of it if you're a writer.

00:46:55.520 --> 00:47:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And with crime fiction, I guess, again, using an economist term, one could say that the

00:47:00.680 --> 00:47:03.480
[Amit Varma]: incentives of a crime writer are very functional.

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:09.000
[Amit Varma]: He has to keep the reader hooked, he has to, you know, the imperative for him is to keep

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:13.480
[Amit Varma]: moving the action forward, but also he wants to paint as rich a world as he can within

00:47:13.480 --> 00:47:14.720
[Amit Varma]: that constraint.

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:16.040
[Guest]: So you do see a lot of...

00:47:16.040 --> 00:47:20.640
[Guest]: And also remember that some of the best crime fiction then ends up being a series with the

00:47:20.640 --> 00:47:26.480
[Guest]: same character having to be true to that same character, but plot changing every time, enough

00:47:26.480 --> 00:47:32.400
[Guest]: of a deepening of character that you will continue to find new things in each book.

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:37.640
[Guest]: So I'm reading a Jack Reacher at the moment, which I think that man is like the kind of

00:47:37.640 --> 00:47:39.960
[Guest]: man I'd like to be someday.

00:47:39.960 --> 00:47:44.320
[Guest]: Just walking off into the wild with one set of clothes and one toothbrush and that's all

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:45.320
[Guest]: he has.

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:49.240
[Guest]: And he just lives every day in that moment.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:53.320
[Guest]: I mean, it's like a philosophy of life, which you don't expect to find in crime fiction,

00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:54.960
[Guest]: which you do here.

00:47:54.960 --> 00:47:57.920
[Guest]: And all of these kinds of... from the P.D.

00:47:57.920 --> 00:48:03.000
[Guest]: James on where it was, it's beautiful, it's literary, and, you know, the individual in

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:08.640
[Guest]: that English countryside is very different from the ex-marine in America.

00:48:08.640 --> 00:48:12.320
[Guest]: But somewhere it's the same hunt for meaning.

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:16.740
[Guest]: It's the same search for the things that will make life worth living.

00:48:16.740 --> 00:48:23.520
[Guest]: And I think as they are in literary fiction, crime fiction articulates that hopelessness

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:28.440
[Guest]: and the need to stay, survive and hope.

00:48:28.440 --> 00:48:33.440
[Guest]: Because every time somebody dies, somebody is trying to find an answer to why.

00:48:33.440 --> 00:48:36.740
[Guest]: And in that finding, you also find a reason to live.

00:48:36.740 --> 00:48:41.200
[Guest]: And I think people underestimate what crime fiction can do to you, not just in terms of

00:48:41.200 --> 00:48:48.680
[Guest]: how to read, but also in terms of what they take away each time from a really sharp novel

00:48:48.680 --> 00:48:50.360
[Guest]: in that genre.

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:53.680
[Guest]: So yeah, why did I just go on and on about crime fiction?

00:48:53.680 --> 00:48:55.480
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's actually a very profound observation.

00:48:55.480 --> 00:49:00.400
[Amit Varma]: And I was reminded, for example, of Sir Wal and Walu, who, of course, you know, the remarkable

00:49:00.400 --> 00:49:05.360
[Amit Varma]: series starting with, I think, Roseanne was the first book and they came at the crime

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:09.520
[Amit Varma]: series, not just with the sense that let's write an interesting crime series, but also

00:49:09.520 --> 00:49:13.560
[Amit Varma]: with a vision of the world and a vision of what society is and should be.

00:49:13.560 --> 00:49:17.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so occasionally, every 50 pages, there'll be this irritating paragraph, which

00:49:17.640 --> 00:49:19.480
[Unknown]: rants against capitalism.

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:26.000
[Amit Varma]: But quite apart from that, it's and I think they set the trend for a lot of the sort of

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:29.640
[Amit Varma]: crime fiction which follows, which kind of brings me to a related question that, you

00:49:29.640 --> 00:49:32.720
[Amit Varma]: know, where is the Indian crime fiction?

00:49:32.720 --> 00:49:36.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I mean, I know there's quite a lot of it, but surely, you know, in different

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:42.640
[Unknown]: disparate sort of ways, Surendra Mohan Pathak kind of way and, you know, stray literary

00:49:42.640 --> 00:49:45.760
[Guest]: attempts here and there, but, you know, we don't have...

00:49:45.760 --> 00:49:49.960
[Guest]: It isn't yet a sort of full fledged segment.

00:49:49.960 --> 00:49:56.800
[Guest]: There have been books, Anita Nair's Gowda series comes to mind, Arjun Gend and his historical

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:57.800
[Guest]: series.

00:49:57.800 --> 00:50:04.320
[Guest]: So, of course, there's writers located in the West who are writing within Indian situations.

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:08.920
[Guest]: I think it's starting up in a more sort of concrete way.

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:15.880
[Guest]: But I worry that the visual world actually is not allowing that to grow so much because

00:50:15.880 --> 00:50:20.320
[Guest]: there's so much great crime, so much great action on your screens all the time, your

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:24.440
[Guest]: Netflix and Prime and whatever else you're doing, watching that.

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:29.720
[Guest]: I feel like a lot of good, possibly good crime writers are probably writing for those spaces

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:37.720
[Guest]: now and are not so interested in the book, which gives them much less in terms of readership

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:41.240
[Guest]: or numbers, as opposed to the viewership.

00:50:41.240 --> 00:50:45.140
[Guest]: And also, of course, in terms of less money, they earn much more writing that same thing

00:50:45.140 --> 00:50:48.960
[Guest]: for somebody else who's going to make a big production out of it.

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:54.000
[Guest]: So I don't know how much perseverance there will be in that community of crime writers.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:55.000
[Guest]: I hope to continue.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in fact, that's a question I was saving for the end.

00:50:57.500 --> 00:51:01.040
[Amit Varma]: So before we go in for a break, I'll ask it anyway, if a little early since you brought

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:06.720
[Amit Varma]: the subject up, that, you know, a lot of creative people, a lot of imaginative people who would

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:12.160
[Amit Varma]: otherwise have taken to writing books now have other options for their creative juices.

00:51:12.160 --> 00:51:17.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, they can work on a web series, they can even go into filmmaking, or, you know,

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:19.200
[Amit Varma]: there are so many options available out there.

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:24.380
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I remember thinking when I first saw The Wire all those years ago, absolutely loving

00:51:24.380 --> 00:51:28.120
[Amit Varma]: it because of its novelistic sweep, the way it slowly unfolds.

00:51:28.120 --> 00:51:31.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's not like a, you know, typically, I think of a film as something like a short

00:51:31.600 --> 00:51:36.080
[Amit Varma]: story that you've got, you know, that one linear strand and maybe one or two others,

00:51:36.080 --> 00:51:37.080
[Amit Varma]: but that's about it.

00:51:37.080 --> 00:51:41.080
[Amit Varma]: But The Wire build this novelistic universe and carries it through for seven seasons.

00:51:41.080 --> 00:51:46.160
[Amit Varma]: But then that also means that people who have the urges to build worlds like that, and to

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:51.700
[Amit Varma]: go that deep and to talk about those things don't necessarily have to turn to pen and

00:51:51.700 --> 00:51:52.700
[Amit Varma]: paper to do it.

00:51:52.700 --> 00:51:53.760
[Amit Varma]: There are other ways.

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:57.320
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you see affecting books in the future?

00:51:57.320 --> 00:51:59.440
[Amit Varma]: You are like, no, there's a space for everything we'll manage.

00:51:59.440 --> 00:52:01.000
[Guest]: I think there's a space for everything.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:05.840
[Guest]: I think there's a space for people who want to write for that space and also write books.

00:52:05.840 --> 00:52:10.640
[Guest]: I also know, Amish, for instance, is a writer I work with as well.

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:15.520
[Guest]: And in this context, I remember Amish saying that he still wants to keep writing books

00:52:15.520 --> 00:52:21.480
[Guest]: because he feels that is his individual space where his mind, his thinking, his philosophy

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.400
[Guest]: of life is what he's working on.

00:52:23.400 --> 00:52:27.800
[Guest]: It isn't what will fit somebody else's idea of what works on screen.

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:31.120
[Guest]: It isn't that there are multiple screenwriters and dialogue writers and all of these people

00:52:31.120 --> 00:52:35.320
[Guest]: who are going to come into the picture and take your idea and make it something else.

00:52:35.320 --> 00:52:41.640
[Guest]: It's like if you want the purity of your own words and your own thoughts, then perhaps

00:52:41.640 --> 00:52:49.160
[Guest]: the book is the only place where you can get that kind of concentrated individuality rather

00:52:49.160 --> 00:52:53.720
[Guest]: than something on screen, which is obviously the effort of multiple minds and multiple

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:54.720
[Guest]: people.

00:52:54.720 --> 00:52:57.640
[Guest]: So apart from the book, I doubt there's any other place.

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:03.160
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I think of like two kinds of tragic opportunity costs that come in.

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:06.840
[Amit Varma]: One, obviously, is that the screen pays so much better.

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:10.480
[Amit Varma]: And once you get drawn into that, and then you start living that lifestyle, also, it

00:53:10.480 --> 00:53:12.840
[Amit Varma]: seems a waste to give it up and write a book.

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And also the other thing that I have found from living in Bombay, though I never myself

00:53:17.240 --> 00:53:22.040
[Amit Varma]: have tried to put a foot in the film world, but what I see around me is that maybe one

00:53:22.040 --> 00:53:24.000
[Unknown]: out of 100 projects will get through.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:28.080
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of the work that a writer does could basically be wasted, either it doesn't get

00:53:28.080 --> 00:53:30.600
[Amit Varma]: made or if it gets made, it gets made badly.

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:34.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's not something you can own up to and years can pass by like that.

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:39.360
[Amit Varma]: While if you write a book, however bad, it is still your own product, like Amish told

00:53:39.360 --> 00:53:41.560
[Amit Varma]: you, that's where his own individuality comes.

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And also, I think what happens very often, and you know, many more writers than me, so

00:53:46.200 --> 00:53:53.240
[Amit Varma]: you'll be able to tell me if I'm, if this observation is valid, is that a lot of writers,

00:53:53.240 --> 00:53:57.680
[Amit Varma]: when they start out aren't necessarily good writers, but they'll muddle through one book

00:53:57.680 --> 00:54:02.320
[Amit Varma]: and they'll muddle through another and then at some point in time, just by doing repeatedly,

00:54:02.320 --> 00:54:03.760
[Amit Varma]: they get better at it.

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:07.560
[Amit Varma]: And that initial self delusion about how good they are, when they weren't good, actually

00:54:07.560 --> 00:54:08.600
[Amit Varma]: makes them good.

00:54:08.600 --> 00:54:11.360
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, you can say they fake it till they make it.

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:13.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and we were talking crime fiction.

00:54:13.400 --> 00:54:18.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are so many crime series I can think of, which start off in a very iffy way.

00:54:18.960 --> 00:54:21.360
[Unknown]: The first two or three books aren't quite there.

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:26.280
[Unknown]: And then the writer solidifies in the voice and then it just becomes something else entirely.

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Siowal and Walu actually being an exception to that, because I think the beginning

00:54:29.680 --> 00:54:30.680
[Guest]: was good.

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:32.040
[Amit Varma]: The beginning was stunning.

00:54:32.040 --> 00:54:33.040
[Amit Varma]: Is there something to that?

00:54:33.040 --> 00:54:37.240
[Amit Varma]: And then is there the danger that the two or three books that a writer might need to

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:39.600
[Amit Varma]: sort of find their feet and become better?

00:54:39.600 --> 00:54:43.760
[Amit Varma]: They don't happen because maybe after the first one, the guy just says, okay, you know,

00:54:43.760 --> 00:54:46.240
[Amit Varma]: let me do that instead.

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:49.840
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, and that's like the show is called the scene in the unseen.

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:53.800
[Amit Varma]: So maybe, you know, that is the unseen that what doesn't happen.

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:58.800
[Guest]: I think that's one of those things in publishing, which has now become a story to remember and

00:54:58.800 --> 00:55:04.280
[Guest]: to hold on to, to prove that things can change, which is you will have a writer who's done

00:55:04.280 --> 00:55:10.240
[Guest]: maybe two books, which haven't sold very much, which are 2000 copies, maybe, and if the editor

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:14.680
[Guest]: and the publisher will persevere with them, then sometimes a third or fourth book might

00:55:14.680 --> 00:55:17.400
[Guest]: hit it so big that there's no looking back.

00:55:17.400 --> 00:55:22.320
[Guest]: I think Bridges of Madison County is one of those stories where the writer did not really

00:55:22.320 --> 00:55:24.000
[Guest]: do all that much.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:28.840
[Guest]: And then suddenly there was this multi million copy seller, and things changed, right?

00:55:28.840 --> 00:55:32.440
[Guest]: Now, if that person had given up at that point and said, I'll go write for another forum,

00:55:32.440 --> 00:55:35.880
[Guest]: or the publisher had said, I'm sorry, I can't afford to keep you any longer.

00:55:35.880 --> 00:55:37.960
[Guest]: Things could have been very, very different.

00:55:37.960 --> 00:55:43.280
[Guest]: But I think there are enough stories in the past, and in our own kind of mythologizing

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:49.480
[Guest]: of the past that allows for people to hold on to hope and say, if not now, the next time

00:55:49.480 --> 00:55:52.200
[Guest]: the next time, and you go on like that.

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:58.160
[Guest]: And as I said, as long as they're not doing just that, as long as they have other sources

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:03.400
[Guest]: of work and income and all of that, they might still persevere because they care deeply enough

00:56:03.400 --> 00:56:04.400
[Guest]: to do this.

00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:08.120
[Guest]: And because those hours that they spend with their characters, and in their own minds and

00:56:08.120 --> 00:56:13.360
[Guest]: on the paper, I think they attach a certain value to it, which they would not give up

00:56:13.360 --> 00:56:14.840
[Guest]: for the world.

00:56:14.840 --> 00:56:20.840
[Guest]: And in that sense, also publishing, I think is a slightly odd and paradoxical space, because

00:56:20.840 --> 00:56:21.880
[Guest]: look at where it comes from.

00:56:21.880 --> 00:56:27.760
[Guest]: You're a writer, you sit alone at your table at your laptop, whatever, and you write quietly,

00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:30.320
[Guest]: for yourself almost.

00:56:30.320 --> 00:56:35.520
[Guest]: When it comes to me as a finished book, I'm sitting there quietly by myself absorbing

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:38.560
[Guest]: this text with nobody else interfering.

00:56:38.560 --> 00:56:40.000
[Guest]: There's no sound, there's nothing.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:41.800
[Guest]: I'm making up the sounds for these people.

00:56:41.800 --> 00:56:43.500
[Guest]: I'm making up the voices.

00:56:43.500 --> 00:56:45.720
[Guest]: I'm breathing in the gaps.

00:56:45.720 --> 00:56:48.960
[Guest]: And I'm providing all the visual atmosphere, everything.

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:51.720
[Guest]: But what is the publisher gearing up for?

00:56:51.720 --> 00:56:56.380
[Guest]: These two isolated acts at the end, these quiet moments.

00:56:56.380 --> 00:57:02.560
[Guest]: And what lies in between is a completely public system of selection, distribution, marketing,

00:57:02.560 --> 00:57:07.920
[Guest]: selling, putting a lot of noise into everything, which has to begin and end in quietness.

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:14.640
[Guest]: And I think that paradox is exactly the nature of all that we do around books, that there

00:57:14.640 --> 00:57:18.660
[Guest]: are always forces pulling completely in opposite directions.

00:57:18.660 --> 00:57:25.440
[Guest]: What one wants to do, what one ends up doing, what comes in between, they're all contradictory.

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:30.680
[Guest]: And yet we have to make peace with this chaos and arrive at something that will last for

00:57:30.680 --> 00:57:31.680
[Guest]: a long time.

00:57:31.680 --> 00:57:37.680
[Guest]: Because what is the difference between that piece of journalism or that bit of movie making?

00:57:37.680 --> 00:57:40.400
[Guest]: You often find that movies can be dated, right?

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:44.600
[Guest]: Because you have a visual, a look to that space.

00:57:44.600 --> 00:57:47.760
[Guest]: And 10 years down, there are people wearing different clothes, there's different things

00:57:47.760 --> 00:57:48.760
[Guest]: happening.

00:57:48.760 --> 00:57:52.560
[Guest]: So either you treat them as classics and working in that time.

00:57:52.560 --> 00:57:57.440
[Guest]: Whereas in a book, like, you know, if I go and watch You've Got Mail Now, which I happen

00:57:57.440 --> 00:58:03.120
[Guest]: to do accidentally the other day, and I thought, oh, this is such a different old world movie,

00:58:03.120 --> 00:58:05.520
[Guest]: you know, everything is old about it.

00:58:05.520 --> 00:58:11.700
[Guest]: But I can read a book, which is Jane Austen in England, in that time.

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:15.560
[Guest]: And because I'm the one who's providing the acoustics for this in my present time, it

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:18.360
[Guest]: will always be a contemporary work.

00:58:18.360 --> 00:58:22.760
[Guest]: Because what I attach to that word, the meaning of that word may have changed over hundreds

00:58:22.760 --> 00:58:24.080
[Guest]: of years.

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:27.140
[Guest]: But what it is now is my word, my meaning.

00:58:27.140 --> 00:58:28.960
[Guest]: So I read it for myself.

00:58:28.960 --> 00:58:34.600
[Guest]: I don't have to stick to the sound or the effects of what is available to me given by

00:58:34.600 --> 00:58:35.920
[Guest]: somebody else.

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:42.280
[Guest]: So in that sense, you reinvent text and reinvent in solitude, what is not possible to reinvent

00:58:42.280 --> 00:58:45.740
[Guest]: when it's a public act offered in public spaces.

00:58:45.740 --> 00:58:48.960
[Guest]: So I think that's what makes publishing special.

00:58:48.960 --> 00:58:54.400
[Guest]: I think it allows you to create work that has the capacity to last in ways that probably

00:58:54.400 --> 00:58:57.720
[Guest]: nothing else does except a great work of art.

00:58:57.720 --> 00:59:03.040
[Guest]: And it's, it's wrong to underestimate the finished that final book, which may seem like

00:59:03.040 --> 00:59:06.800
[Guest]: a dead object to a lot of people, but I think it's ever going to go away.

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:10.400
[Guest]: I mean, the nature of paper might change, it might come from another kind of recyclable

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:12.620
[Guest]: recycled paper than it is today.

00:59:12.620 --> 00:59:18.000
[Guest]: And I cannot for the life of me imagine a world where people would not value quietness,

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:24.320
[Guest]: solitude, your own ideas, your own mind, and to put yourself at the center of your world,

00:59:24.320 --> 00:59:26.360
[Guest]: which is what everyone aspires to do.

00:59:26.360 --> 00:59:32.680
[Guest]: A book allows you the room and the system almost to say this is all right, this is a

00:59:32.680 --> 00:59:34.640
[Guest]: good space for you to be in.

00:59:34.640 --> 00:59:38.400
[Guest]: And there's nothing wrong with wanting to be quietly with yourself.

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:39.880
[Guest]: And the book is part of that experience.

00:59:39.880 --> 00:59:41.360
[Amit Varma]: No, I completely agree with you.

00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:45.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you've described the magic of reading formal eloquently than I could manage.

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:49.960
[Amit Varma]: But then there is also that other thing that it is not quite true that unlike a film, a

00:59:49.960 --> 00:59:55.760
[Amit Varma]: book doesn't date or change in what it brings to the reader, because what I find increasingly

00:59:55.760 --> 01:00:01.960
[Amit Varma]: happening and often to my distress is that there is an overlay of contemporary politics

01:00:01.960 --> 01:00:04.840
[Amit Varma]: being applied to books of the past and the way you read them.

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:09.800
[Amit Varma]: For example, in it, but in who we both grew up with, and, you know, a golly borg, and

01:00:09.800 --> 01:00:13.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, all this talk of racism and white privilege and so on.

01:00:13.840 --> 01:00:19.400
[Amit Varma]: And to some extent, I understand that as we evolve as people and our prisms and our values

01:00:19.400 --> 01:00:22.480
[Amit Varma]: evolve that will naturally affect the way that we read.

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:26.880
[Amit Varma]: On the other extreme, I sometimes think that we go too far in doing this by overlaying

01:00:26.880 --> 01:00:31.680
[Amit Varma]: this veneer of contemporary political values on an age and a time when they didn't really

01:00:31.680 --> 01:00:36.760
[Amit Varma]: exist and you sometimes just have to give the author the benefit of her contemporaneity.

01:00:36.760 --> 01:00:38.760
[Guest]: Yes, no, I agree with you entirely.

01:00:38.760 --> 01:00:42.480
[Guest]: I think one has to learn to read things within their context.

01:00:42.480 --> 01:00:44.320
[Guest]: And that is the most important thing.

01:00:44.320 --> 01:00:47.440
[Guest]: Without context, you have nothing just as you have your own context that writer had

01:00:47.440 --> 01:00:51.000
[Guest]: theirs and you have to build bridges between them.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:55.680
[Guest]: So I think the way to tackle that is really not to say don't read, but to say, come up

01:00:55.680 --> 01:00:57.160
[Guest]: with reinterpretations.

01:00:57.160 --> 01:01:02.360
[Guest]: For instance, for me, in terms of reading, one of the vital moments of discovery I remember

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:05.600
[Guest]: was Jean Gris' White Sargasso Sea.

01:01:05.600 --> 01:01:07.160
[Guest]: I had read nothing like it before.

01:01:07.160 --> 01:01:11.240
[Guest]: I had not realized you could even do this.

01:01:11.240 --> 01:01:16.480
[Guest]: And the reimagining of that character just, I mean, it was a hugely political act.

01:01:16.480 --> 01:01:18.320
[Guest]: It was a deeply feminist act.

01:01:18.320 --> 01:01:22.720
[Guest]: It was every ism you can think of was in that slim book.

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:27.560
[Guest]: And that, I think, is what I would value that somebody says, I don't agree with that worldview

01:01:27.560 --> 01:01:29.520
[Guest]: of that writer who wrote it in that time.

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:31.920
[Guest]: Yes, of course, it was a product of that time.

01:01:31.920 --> 01:01:37.600
[Guest]: But let me think about it from my time and see how I might tell it differently and encourage

01:01:37.600 --> 01:01:42.880
[Guest]: and inspire other people to read it differently and leave that old text alone for what it

01:01:42.880 --> 01:01:43.880
[Guest]: was.

01:01:43.880 --> 01:01:47.200
[Guest]: Let the Mahabharata be the Mahabharata of whoever wrote it then.

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:48.720
[Guest]: You tell your tellings now.

01:01:48.720 --> 01:01:54.920
[Guest]: You prioritize and centralize whoever you want to and write it for your time.

01:01:54.920 --> 01:02:02.880
[Guest]: But I agree with you that censoring and re-editing old texts for sanitizing or for concealing

01:02:02.880 --> 01:02:06.640
[Guest]: a truth that is valuable in itself.

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:11.320
[Guest]: And sometimes just knowing that that's what was done is enough to make you want to think

01:02:11.320 --> 01:02:13.560
[Guest]: never do that in your own time.

01:02:13.560 --> 01:02:17.600
[Guest]: I think that is a mistake to erase the past in that way.

01:02:17.600 --> 01:02:20.280
[Amit Varma]: We'll take a quick commercial break.

