01:04:57.480 --> 01:04:58.680
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:04:58.680 --> 01:05:01.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with PK Karthika about Indian publishing.

01:05:01.680 --> 01:05:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Karthika, you were just telling me about how in 97 when Arundhati Roy hit the Indian publishing

01:05:08.520 --> 01:05:13.520
[Amit Varma]: scene, everything kind of changed for Indian publishing.

01:05:13.520 --> 01:05:16.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:24.160
[Guest]: I remember that it was unusual in that there was a story attached to how she had nearly

01:05:24.160 --> 01:05:29.520
[Guest]: published with a publisher in India and then not published with them for personal reasons.

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:33.360
[Guest]: And how there was so much excitement about her finding an agent who was so thrilled by

01:05:33.360 --> 01:05:38.080
[Guest]: it that he flew to India to meet her.

01:05:38.080 --> 01:05:41.400
[Guest]: These were all quite extraordinary.

01:05:41.400 --> 01:05:44.680
[Guest]: They were extraordinary in that time that there were things like that happening around

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:45.680
[Guest]: us, you know.

01:05:45.680 --> 01:05:49.960
[Guest]: So it was hard to understand, to grasp at that time.

01:05:49.960 --> 01:05:54.560
[Guest]: It was only later, after everything played out, that you realized how significant all

01:05:54.560 --> 01:05:56.080
[Guest]: this was.

01:05:56.080 --> 01:06:04.360
[Guest]: But at that time, it was like a new wave of confidence for writers and for editors and

01:06:04.360 --> 01:06:09.960
[Guest]: for readers and for just about everyone, because it was like a ratification of and a validation

01:06:09.960 --> 01:06:17.840
[Guest]: of what was considered to be literary by us, what was considered to be good writing, what

01:06:17.840 --> 01:06:18.840
[Guest]: was publishable.

01:06:18.840 --> 01:06:22.960
[Guest]: I mean, if all of these things culminated in a book that won in those days the biggest

01:06:22.960 --> 01:06:26.880
[Guest]: prize of all in literature in the English speaking world, then we had to be doing something

01:06:26.880 --> 01:06:27.880
[Guest]: right.

01:06:27.880 --> 01:06:29.640
[Guest]: I mean, the writers had to be doing something right.

01:06:29.640 --> 01:06:31.520
[Guest]: Readers were getting something right.

01:06:31.520 --> 01:06:33.160
[Guest]: Publishing houses were doing this right.

01:06:33.160 --> 01:06:36.840
[Guest]: Though, of course, the story of that is that a little publishing house was actually set

01:06:36.840 --> 01:06:42.200
[Guest]: up to publish that book because she wanted that to happen, which in itself was unusual,

01:06:42.200 --> 01:06:43.200
[Guest]: right?

01:06:43.200 --> 01:06:48.120
[Guest]: That you have so much confidence in one book that you would set up a system to make that

01:06:48.120 --> 01:06:49.840
[Guest]: happen.

01:06:49.840 --> 01:06:53.240
[Guest]: So a lot of things changed with that.

01:06:53.240 --> 01:06:59.760
[Guest]: It also meant that in a strange way, we started getting clones of Arundhati Roy, submitting

01:06:59.760 --> 01:07:01.560
[Guest]: manuscript left, right and center.

01:07:01.560 --> 01:07:08.080
[Guest]: Basically everyone was writing novels about Kerala, about family, about relationships

01:07:08.080 --> 01:07:13.640
[Guest]: set within an India that was not really a westernized India.

01:07:13.640 --> 01:07:17.580
[Guest]: So many new directions seem to open up.

01:07:17.580 --> 01:07:24.920
[Guest]: At the same time, I think the problem also that it gave us was this firm notion that

01:07:24.920 --> 01:07:29.760
[Guest]: that literary novel of that kind was the thing that had to be.

01:07:29.760 --> 01:07:36.120
[Guest]: So for instance, in the UK, a lot of writers were suddenly given large advances because

01:07:36.120 --> 01:07:40.720
[Guest]: they were all going to be like the next Booker Prize winning novelist.

01:07:40.720 --> 01:07:44.480
[Guest]: And large advances suddenly came into the picture in which they hadn't earlier.

01:07:44.480 --> 01:07:49.720
[Guest]: I mean, Penguin was still one of the few publishing houses then that was giving advances to every

01:07:49.720 --> 01:07:53.440
[Guest]: writer, but a lot of publishing didn't.

01:07:53.440 --> 01:07:59.760
[Guest]: And if you think about it, I almost wish it hadn't changed, because think about publishing

01:07:59.760 --> 01:08:04.760
[Guest]: as a business model, and it is deeply flawed.

01:08:04.760 --> 01:08:09.800
[Guest]: You are writing a book, which you haven't like perhaps written only a proposal for you

01:08:09.800 --> 01:08:12.120
[Guest]: haven't really written very much off.

01:08:12.120 --> 01:08:13.880
[Guest]: I am an editor in a publishing house.

01:08:13.880 --> 01:08:16.880
[Guest]: And I'm saying to you, I want to publish this book when it's done.

01:08:16.880 --> 01:08:20.080
[Guest]: This could be two years from now, three years from now, whatever.

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:25.080
[Guest]: And I'm going to give you this money as a kind of ceiling of an agreement that you will

01:08:25.080 --> 01:08:26.160
[Guest]: eventually finish this.

01:08:26.160 --> 01:08:32.000
[Guest]: So I'm investing money in something of which there is nothing to show at the moment.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.560
[Guest]: And then two years down the line, maybe three years down the line, you will give me a manuscript,

01:08:35.560 --> 01:08:40.000
[Guest]: which I will publish in another six months, eight months a year, for which I will then

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:45.680
[Guest]: get paid by the market in this endless cycle of no payments or near payments, which could

01:08:45.680 --> 01:08:49.680
[Guest]: be within three months or six months or eight months or a year.

01:08:49.680 --> 01:08:54.120
[Guest]: At the end of a year or two years, I might be sent all these physical copies back from

01:08:54.120 --> 01:08:56.680
[Guest]: the market saying they were never sold.

01:08:56.680 --> 01:08:59.120
[Guest]: And my investment was made three years ago.

01:08:59.120 --> 01:09:04.120
[Guest]: And at the end of that period, I've got nothing to show except some returns, which then are

01:09:04.120 --> 01:09:08.640
[Guest]: in the warehouse and which one might be forced to, you know, destroy because they're shop

01:09:08.640 --> 01:09:12.040
[Guest]: soiled or can't be resold or whatever.

01:09:12.040 --> 01:09:17.400
[Guest]: So everything is strange and beats logic.

01:09:17.400 --> 01:09:22.360
[Guest]: I don't know of any other industry that works in this manner, which defies logic and defies

01:09:22.360 --> 01:09:24.880
[Guest]: the odds and still continues to survive.

01:09:24.880 --> 01:09:29.720
[Guest]: And the strange thing is that from then on to now, we have found no other way to do this.

01:09:29.720 --> 01:09:37.000
[Guest]: We continue to be in the cycle of investment without possibly any sign of return for the

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:38.880
[Guest]: foreseeable future.

01:09:38.880 --> 01:09:45.080
[Guest]: So in some ways, I guess it began in that period when big advances seemed all right,

01:09:45.080 --> 01:09:48.880
[Guest]: because you thought you had this large print run that was possible at the end of it and

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:52.760
[Guest]: large lakhs of readers who would want to read that copy.

01:09:52.760 --> 01:09:57.160
[Guest]: So from what might have been like a 15,000 rupee advance, which was very standard in

01:09:57.160 --> 01:10:01.400
[Guest]: those days, I remember even like the best international writers who had publishers in

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:06.040
[Guest]: the US and the UK, you would write out a contract where it's a 20,000 rupees advance.

01:10:06.040 --> 01:10:09.400
[Guest]: And that was fine, because that was all really you hoped to earn.

01:10:09.400 --> 01:10:14.240
[Guest]: Suddenly you were adding zeros to that and you were saying, oh, we should do two lakhs.

01:10:14.240 --> 01:10:18.840
[Guest]: And we all just were banking on the fact that something would take off.

01:10:18.840 --> 01:10:24.600
[Guest]: So where we were much more careful and cautious and realistic, it became a little bit more

01:10:24.600 --> 01:10:26.600
[Guest]: of a gamble.

01:10:26.600 --> 01:10:30.560
[Guest]: And because there was enough competition by then and other publishing houses were setting

01:10:30.560 --> 01:10:35.720
[Guest]: up and there was more everyone trying to, you know, zero in on that little pool of writers

01:10:35.720 --> 01:10:39.160
[Guest]: that was there in the English language at that time.

01:10:39.160 --> 01:10:42.920
[Guest]: Everyone was trying to up the other and give a little bit more money to get that writer

01:10:42.920 --> 01:10:44.280
[Guest]: in the book.

01:10:44.280 --> 01:10:51.960
[Guest]: So we ended up where we are now, which is very unrealistic figures, unrealistic estimations

01:10:51.960 --> 01:11:00.520
[Guest]: of sale and very little to show at the end of it as proof that this system works.

01:11:00.520 --> 01:11:05.520
[Guest]: So there was a time when I said everything changed positively when the book happened

01:11:05.520 --> 01:11:06.760
[Guest]: to us.

01:11:06.760 --> 01:11:11.400
[Guest]: But after that many years, I'm beginning to think there were problems that came off that,

01:11:11.400 --> 01:11:14.000
[Guest]: which we are now discovering the depth of.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:18.920
[Amit Varma]: So let me just try to sort of think aloud a little bit and unpack this whole effect.

01:11:18.920 --> 01:11:23.840
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, it kind of goes back to that earlier issue of heuristics that we talk about that

01:11:23.840 --> 01:11:27.520
[Amit Varma]: how do you decide what is a good book and how do you decide what to commission and what

01:11:27.520 --> 01:11:29.400
[Amit Varma]: kind of books to change.

01:11:29.400 --> 01:11:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And I guess what happens with the God of Small Things is that there's suddenly the survivorship

01:11:33.600 --> 01:11:39.580
[Amit Varma]: bias where there is this book written in expressionistic language set in an exotic locale that seems

01:11:39.580 --> 01:11:44.000
[Amit Varma]: to work and therefore because that one book has done so well and won the booker, then

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:48.280
[Amit Varma]: it is natural for publishers to want more of the same and you give advances chasing

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:52.920
[Amit Varma]: that and because in publishing, unlike in other businesses, like for example, web series

01:11:52.920 --> 01:11:57.320
[Amit Varma]: is a commission today pretty much the same way, but you know, the lifeline is much shorter.

01:11:57.320 --> 01:11:59.900
[Unknown]: They play out in a much shorter span of time.

01:11:59.900 --> 01:12:03.240
[Amit Varma]: And I guess with publishing is taking two or three years and therefore for two or three

01:12:03.240 --> 01:12:07.120
[Amit Varma]: years, you don't know that your investments been a waste and you have a lot of books in

01:12:07.120 --> 01:12:11.240
[Amit Varma]: that language about you know, those kind of things coming out and they are wasted and

01:12:11.240 --> 01:12:15.040
[Amit Varma]: what also that seems to do is it seems to have what economists would call the crowding

01:12:15.040 --> 01:12:20.600
[Amit Varma]: out effect that because there is so much money chasing this particular kind of book, which

01:12:20.600 --> 01:12:25.080
[Amit Varma]: there is, you know, the notion that this is a kind of book which will win awards and which

01:12:25.080 --> 01:12:29.280
[Amit Varma]: will sell and which will bring glory and so on and so forth, that perhaps there is less

01:12:29.280 --> 01:12:34.880
[Amit Varma]: money left to chase or left to fund other writers who are writing different kinds of

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:35.880
[Guest]: books.

01:12:35.880 --> 01:12:38.800
[Amit Varma]: Is that sort of an accurate summation of what kind of went down?

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:39.800
[Guest]: I think so.

01:12:39.800 --> 01:12:41.200
[Guest]: I think that's what happened.

01:12:41.200 --> 01:12:46.600
[Guest]: And in the process, we also discovered that there were some great writers amongst us and

01:12:46.600 --> 01:12:50.600
[Guest]: some great books were published and a lot of first time writers found support in a way

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:55.880
[Guest]: they may not have otherwise, which I think is the most valuable thing that happened.

01:12:55.880 --> 01:13:02.560
[Guest]: Because then the next generation of writers had a different felicity with the language,

01:13:02.560 --> 01:13:08.720
[Guest]: a different brashness with the language, wrote for the world more confidently without doubting

01:13:08.720 --> 01:13:10.200
[Guest]: themselves in the same way.

01:13:10.200 --> 01:13:14.460
[Guest]: Not, I mean, I think all writers doubt themselves, but not doubting that they could be as good

01:13:14.460 --> 01:13:16.320
[Guest]: as anybody else.

01:13:16.320 --> 01:13:22.840
[Guest]: And that was really, really the best outcome of that period.

01:13:22.840 --> 01:13:30.080
[Guest]: But what that crowding out did, I think, was also very important to notice that there were

01:13:30.080 --> 01:13:35.920
[Guest]: certain kinds of writing that never did come out enough, that people didn't pay enough

01:13:35.920 --> 01:13:38.960
[Guest]: attention to or put value to.

01:13:38.960 --> 01:13:45.000
[Guest]: And that is why I think the next shift is Chetan Bhagat, because that was, to my mind,

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:52.840
[Guest]: looking back, that was a direct revolt against the ivory tower existence of that English

01:13:52.840 --> 01:14:00.400
[Guest]: literary space, where the reader was a certain kind of person, a privileged person, a person

01:14:00.400 --> 01:14:05.960
[Guest]: whose notions of what was acceptable and civilized was very different.

01:14:05.960 --> 01:14:10.480
[Guest]: And where there was no recognition of the fact that there are multiple cultures and

01:14:10.480 --> 01:14:17.360
[Guest]: languages and so many other things happening outside of the metropolitan Indian city.

01:14:17.360 --> 01:14:25.320
[Guest]: And then I think we got to a place where it wasn't about what comes before, that is the

01:14:25.320 --> 01:14:31.040
[Guest]: writing, the publishing, the editing, it was about what happens after, which is the marketing.

01:14:31.040 --> 01:14:36.360
[Guest]: And that shift really redefined everything in publishing as well.

01:14:36.360 --> 01:14:40.880
[Amit Varma]: And I guess what Chetan did was, of course, one, he took themes which resonated with common

01:14:40.880 --> 01:14:45.960
[Amit Varma]: people like life in an IIT or, you know, and interstate love affairs or whatever the kind

01:14:45.960 --> 01:14:50.160
[Amit Varma]: of topics that he's chosen, sort of resonate with many more people.

01:14:50.160 --> 01:14:55.320
[Amit Varma]: And second, there was a marketing and did that sort of the massive success that Chetan

01:14:55.320 --> 01:15:00.200
[Amit Varma]: had and then that people that are similar writers after him also build their markets,

01:15:00.200 --> 01:15:02.840
[Amit Varma]: Ravinders and Durjoy's and all that.

01:15:02.840 --> 01:15:08.360
[Amit Varma]: Did that then change those within publishing to sort of re examine your own values of what

01:15:08.360 --> 01:15:11.160
[Amit Varma]: makes a good book and what kind of book are you looking for?

01:15:11.160 --> 01:15:15.200
[Amit Varma]: Do you start reading a little differently and asking yourself more questions?

01:15:15.200 --> 01:15:18.040
[Guest]: Absolutely, all of that.

01:15:18.040 --> 01:15:22.040
[Guest]: When Chetan first did the rounds of the publishing houses, I mean, everyone knows that he was

01:15:22.040 --> 01:15:25.200
[Guest]: turned down by most people who didn't see this.

01:15:25.200 --> 01:15:30.720
[Guest]: I think the fact that a writer had a PowerPoint presentation about how to sell the book, it

01:15:30.720 --> 01:15:35.760
[Guest]: just went against the notions of every literary editor in any publishing house because they

01:15:35.760 --> 01:15:40.760
[Guest]: thought that it had to come as a consequence of a great book you sold.

01:15:40.760 --> 01:15:42.880
[Guest]: It was all supposed to be organic.

01:15:42.880 --> 01:15:48.280
[Guest]: There was like you couldn't put a system in place to to manufacture sales.

01:15:48.280 --> 01:15:50.400
[Guest]: You know, these were all not good words.

01:15:50.400 --> 01:15:52.960
[Guest]: They didn't exist in our vocabulary.

01:15:52.960 --> 01:15:57.040
[Guest]: We were supposed to find the best and the best would automatically sell, which we know

01:15:57.040 --> 01:15:58.360
[Guest]: is not the truth at all.

01:15:58.360 --> 01:16:00.080
[Guest]: There was a certain naivety in publishing.

01:16:00.080 --> 01:16:05.960
[Guest]: There were a lot of young people in it with little experience of publishing who just,

01:16:05.960 --> 01:16:10.020
[Guest]: I think, lived in slightly idealistic spaces in their own heads and everything around them

01:16:10.020 --> 01:16:14.640
[Guest]: supported that idealism that said a good thing would find its way to the world in the right

01:16:14.640 --> 01:16:15.640
[Guest]: way.

01:16:15.640 --> 01:16:18.360
[Guest]: Chetan changed that for sure.

01:16:18.360 --> 01:16:20.320
[Guest]: There was a lot of resistance even later.

01:16:20.320 --> 01:16:22.920
[Guest]: Everyone wanted to, I think, think it was a flash in the pan.

01:16:22.920 --> 01:16:24.440
[Guest]: And yes, of course, this happened.

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:30.160
[Guest]: But there was cynicism in that people questioned the ways of selling.

01:16:30.160 --> 01:16:32.640
[Guest]: And was this the right way to sell and market a book?

01:16:32.640 --> 01:16:34.880
[Guest]: And can a book be a product?

01:16:34.880 --> 01:16:40.880
[Guest]: So marketing and editorials would get into fisticuffs about marketing saying, well, you

01:16:40.880 --> 01:16:43.520
[Guest]: know, it is also like a button or a piece of chocolate.

01:16:43.520 --> 01:16:46.320
[Guest]: You've got to sell it and you've got to find the right ways to sell it.

01:16:46.320 --> 01:16:50.480
[Guest]: An editorial would probably think this was really not the right way to talk about it.

01:16:50.480 --> 01:16:54.360
[Guest]: I still know editors and senior editors in publishing houses who will say, we don't like

01:16:54.360 --> 01:16:55.360
[Guest]: the word content.

01:16:55.360 --> 01:16:57.600
[Unknown]: We don't like the word consumer.

01:16:57.600 --> 01:16:59.120
[Guest]: Can we please talk about readers?

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:03.960
[Guest]: Can we talk about how we used to be at one time and, you know, not change it so drastically?

01:17:03.960 --> 01:17:07.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this kind of snobbery is rife in that ultimate performative space Twitter,

01:17:07.840 --> 01:17:12.080
[Amit Varma]: where people will say, oh, you cannot refer to books as content or whatever.

01:17:12.080 --> 01:17:15.280
[Guest]: Yeah, unfortunately, that doesn't really hold good anymore.

01:17:15.280 --> 01:17:16.400
[Guest]: We've got to rethink it.

01:17:16.400 --> 01:17:23.520
[Guest]: And I think that kind of rethinking was forced by the success of the writers that we mentioned.

01:17:23.520 --> 01:17:27.080
[Guest]: Because then you also discovered a second market, second, third, whatever you want to

01:17:27.080 --> 01:17:30.040
[Guest]: call it, which is outside the metros.

01:17:30.040 --> 01:17:34.600
[Guest]: Somebody had imagined that these books were going to reach readers in places outside Delhi,

01:17:34.600 --> 01:17:36.720
[Guest]: Bombay, Madras, whatever.

01:17:36.720 --> 01:17:39.120
[Guest]: And suddenly you're saying, who are these people?

01:17:39.120 --> 01:17:40.760
[Guest]: Who are these people that we never think about?

01:17:40.760 --> 01:17:43.080
[Guest]: Who we never planned for?

01:17:43.080 --> 01:17:44.880
[Guest]: What do they want to read?

01:17:44.880 --> 01:17:48.200
[Guest]: And what is their comfort level with the language?

01:17:48.200 --> 01:17:54.880
[Guest]: With what is the tradition of reading or the background in reading they're bringing to

01:17:54.880 --> 01:17:55.880
[Guest]: this?

01:17:55.880 --> 01:18:00.200
[Guest]: And for so long, we'd assumed that the reader who reads our literary fiction or any fiction

01:18:00.200 --> 01:18:02.800
[Guest]: at all was already trained in the classics.

01:18:02.800 --> 01:18:05.880
[Guest]: In some way, they had read a lot before they came to it.

01:18:05.880 --> 01:18:10.120
[Guest]: So you always had to better, you always had to like ride on those shoulders and create

01:18:10.120 --> 01:18:15.400
[Guest]: an Indian text that came from the Western liberal tradition.

01:18:15.400 --> 01:18:18.400
[Guest]: Which if you think about it, is pretty nonsensical.

01:18:18.400 --> 01:18:22.680
[Guest]: Because your experience is rooted here, your writing has to come from here, which is the

01:18:22.680 --> 01:18:24.840
[Guest]: other marvelous thing that Arundhati did, right?

01:18:24.840 --> 01:18:31.080
[Guest]: She wrote from here, off here, with language homegrown in many ways, experience homegrown.

01:18:31.080 --> 01:18:34.640
[Guest]: So it changed everything then.

01:18:34.640 --> 01:18:38.880
[Guest]: And when you discover that people wanted to read writers like Chetan, because they also

01:18:38.880 --> 01:18:44.360
[Guest]: wanted to be seen to be reading, seen to be reading in English, seen to be carrying a

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:48.520
[Guest]: book that was written in English and saying, I have the ability to read this.

01:18:48.520 --> 01:18:55.600
[Guest]: This was bringing a different sense of how society worked, how individuals wanted to

01:18:55.600 --> 01:19:02.760
[Guest]: be seen and how the entire tradition of writing that we had thought we were building on was

01:19:02.760 --> 01:19:04.240
[Guest]: completely wrong.

01:19:04.240 --> 01:19:07.960
[Guest]: These were people who may have read a lot of writing in other languages and then come

01:19:07.960 --> 01:19:09.400
[Guest]: to Chetan.

01:19:09.400 --> 01:19:14.960
[Guest]: So their idea of a text and their idea of what makes a text work could be very different

01:19:14.960 --> 01:19:19.920
[Guest]: from what an English speaking, English reading editor in a publishing house thinks of as

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:22.080
[Guest]: the foundation for a book.

01:19:22.080 --> 01:19:24.680
[Guest]: These were completely drastic rethinks that had to be done.

01:19:24.680 --> 01:19:29.480
[Guest]: And I don't know if we've succeeded even now, because that lack of diversity within publishing

01:19:29.480 --> 01:19:34.960
[Guest]: houses, the kind of people who come to publishing in English language, there is still that sense

01:19:34.960 --> 01:19:42.640
[Guest]: of, I don't want to call it snobbery, because that's belittling what is much more than that.

01:19:42.640 --> 01:19:45.840
[Guest]: There's a sensibility there, which is different.

01:19:45.840 --> 01:19:49.160
[Guest]: But I think editors are coming to terms with that, publishing houses are coming to terms

01:19:49.160 --> 01:19:50.360
[Guest]: with that.

01:19:50.360 --> 01:19:54.400
[Guest]: And what is helping is bilinguality or trilinguality.

01:19:54.400 --> 01:20:00.120
[Guest]: I think a lot of editors in publishing houses now have access to more than the English language

01:20:00.120 --> 01:20:05.000
[Guest]: and are consciously aware that they have to be part of other worlds and other cultures

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:10.680
[Guest]: to be better at their job in an English language publishing space, which is a completely different

01:20:10.680 --> 01:20:15.480
[Guest]: thing from what it was 15 years ago, where you kept looking for that Western educated

01:20:15.480 --> 01:20:22.200
[Guest]: Oxfordian, you know, like the experience had to be of being able to access sophisticated

01:20:22.200 --> 01:20:26.000
[Guest]: narrative in the West in order to be able to do well here.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:32.080
[Guest]: But now I think most of us who speak to colleagues in editorial departments, all of us value

01:20:32.080 --> 01:20:38.040
[Guest]: the person who can tell us more about Malayalam or Telugu or Tamil or Bengali than someone

01:20:38.040 --> 01:20:42.000
[Guest]: who can tell us what the best of American writing is doing now, because that we know

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:43.320
[Guest]: how to access as well.

01:20:43.320 --> 01:20:49.080
[Guest]: But this is much more that you have to be of that place.

01:20:49.080 --> 01:20:52.340
[Guest]: And not too many learn to occupy that space.

01:20:52.340 --> 01:20:57.240
[Guest]: So that diversity is bringing in the next level of thinking we need.

01:20:57.240 --> 01:21:01.400
[Amit Varma]: I guess, you know, when the future of Indian literature is written in the future by a future

01:21:01.400 --> 01:21:07.040
[Amit Varma]: historian, she will inevitably have to grapple with the question all historians grapple with,

01:21:07.040 --> 01:21:11.960
[Amit Varma]: which is a great man theory of history, Carlisle theory that you know, do great men, Carlisle,

01:21:11.960 --> 01:21:16.600
[Amit Varma]: of course, use the term great men, but do great people shape history or are there currents

01:21:16.600 --> 01:21:21.520
[Amit Varma]: of history which are independent and, you know, whatever great people emerged from that

01:21:21.520 --> 01:21:26.200
[Amit Varma]: as purely happenstance and in that regard, I'm sort of wondering that, you know, the

01:21:26.200 --> 01:21:32.680
[Amit Varma]: massive explosion of readers outside the metros in small town India at around the time Chetan

01:21:32.680 --> 01:21:38.760
[Amit Varma]: Bhagat came up, would you say that that hunger for reading English and being seen to be reading

01:21:38.760 --> 01:21:44.320
[Amit Varma]: English was an inevitable consequence of post liberalization India the way it was developing

01:21:44.320 --> 01:21:48.720
[Amit Varma]: in any case in Chetan just happened to be at the right time at the right place?

01:21:48.720 --> 01:21:55.920
[Amit Varma]: Or do you think Chetan really did play a huge part in sort of making it fructify sooner

01:21:55.920 --> 01:21:57.480
[Amit Varma]: than it perhaps would have?

01:21:57.480 --> 01:21:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Do you have a sense?

01:21:58.480 --> 01:21:59.680
[Guest]: I think it's that old thing.

01:21:59.680 --> 01:22:04.480
[Guest]: If we if Chetan hadn't come along, we would have had to invent a Chetan because the time

01:22:04.480 --> 01:22:13.160
[Guest]: was such that something had to shift for us to find our own bearings and not allow it

01:22:13.160 --> 01:22:16.720
[Guest]: to drift into a space where nobody actually belonged.

01:22:16.720 --> 01:22:21.120
[Guest]: And nobody could anchor it in anything but a space outside.

01:22:21.120 --> 01:22:26.640
[Guest]: So what Chetan did was, I think, recognize what was going on and feel strongly enough

01:22:26.640 --> 01:22:30.200
[Guest]: about it to put himself on the line because I don't think it was an easy job to go out

01:22:30.200 --> 01:22:34.080
[Guest]: there and say I'm a writer is always a tough job to go out there and say I'm a writer who

01:22:34.080 --> 01:22:37.880
[Guest]: thinks I can sell a hundred thousand copies at a time when nobody did that.

01:22:37.880 --> 01:22:42.560
[Guest]: That is audacity of the sort that you would not even dream of for the most part, but he

01:22:42.560 --> 01:22:47.280
[Guest]: did and that allowed everything to change quite dramatically.

01:22:47.280 --> 01:22:50.520
[Guest]: So I would think it's a combination of things and if it hadn't been Chetan, someone else

01:22:50.520 --> 01:22:52.160
[Guest]: would at some point have done it.

01:22:52.160 --> 01:22:57.040
[Guest]: Like later Amish came along and transformed that other space of mythology and retellings.

01:22:57.040 --> 01:23:00.200
[Guest]: If he hadn't, I guess somebody else would have.

01:23:00.200 --> 01:23:07.240
[Guest]: But the important thing I think is that now things have settled into a space where that

01:23:07.240 --> 01:23:08.760
[Guest]: wave is over.

01:23:08.760 --> 01:23:14.160
[Guest]: And interestingly, very few have followed in that space.

01:23:14.160 --> 01:23:19.200
[Guest]: Like you still have Chetan Bhagat at the top of the bestseller charts week after week after

01:23:19.200 --> 01:23:20.200
[Guest]: week.

01:23:20.200 --> 01:23:21.200
[Guest]: It is quite extraordinary.

01:23:21.200 --> 01:23:25.760
[Guest]: A decade in, he's still on top.

01:23:25.760 --> 01:23:32.760
[Guest]: And that so many other writers who tried to write like him haven't stayed there.

01:23:32.760 --> 01:23:37.560
[Guest]: So it seems now that that time too is perhaps over.

01:23:37.560 --> 01:23:42.680
[Guest]: We are waiting for the next thing to happen, but nobody knows what that next thing is.

01:23:42.680 --> 01:23:44.680
[Guest]: And it's very difficult to predict what it could be.

01:23:44.680 --> 01:23:51.440
[Guest]: And also, as we can see in front of us that reading itself is becoming challenging, writing

01:23:51.440 --> 01:23:53.400
[Guest]: is becoming challenging in this space.

01:23:53.400 --> 01:23:57.840
[Guest]: What is it that is going to take that space and suddenly sweep all the rules away?

01:23:57.840 --> 01:23:59.560
[Amit Varma]: One doesn't know, but it's going to come at some point.

01:23:59.560 --> 01:24:01.560
[Amit Varma]: Where is the Chetan Bhagat who will disrupt?

01:24:01.560 --> 01:24:06.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, one possible reason for why Chetan continues to be where he is, of course, is

01:24:06.480 --> 01:24:11.480
[Amit Varma]: that he's almost become like a self-reinforcing meme in the sense that he is a person for

01:24:11.480 --> 01:24:13.960
[Amit Varma]: a certain class of people, a certain category of people.

01:24:13.960 --> 01:24:15.360
[Unknown]: And it is cool to read.

01:24:15.360 --> 01:24:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that self reinforces itself that, you know, there are households which

01:24:19.520 --> 01:24:21.440
[Amit Varma]: have only six books.

01:24:21.440 --> 01:24:24.720
[Amit Varma]: And earlier back in the day, they would be like they'll have Paulo Coelho and they'll

01:24:24.720 --> 01:24:25.720
[Amit Varma]: have whatever.

01:24:25.720 --> 01:24:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And now Chetan Bhagat is always a mandatory part of that.

01:24:28.440 --> 01:24:29.880
[Amit Varma]: And this reinforces itself.

01:24:29.880 --> 01:24:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not saying this with any trace of derision.

01:24:32.320 --> 01:24:36.000
[Amit Varma]: It is better for a household to have six books and to have no books at all.

01:24:36.000 --> 01:24:38.240
[Amit Varma]: And this is fairly remarkable.

01:24:38.240 --> 01:24:43.240
[Amit Varma]: This friend of mine who lives in Hyderabad, in fact, and he is often on the admissions

01:24:43.240 --> 01:24:45.860
[Amit Varma]: committee of different IIMs and so on.

01:24:45.860 --> 01:24:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And he told me that whenever he's on an interview panel, he'll always ask the person a question,

01:24:49.920 --> 01:24:51.400
[Unknown]: what are your hobbies?

01:24:51.400 --> 01:24:56.160
[Amit Varma]: And whenever they say reading, which apparently 60, more than 60% of them do, his follow up

01:24:56.160 --> 01:24:59.680
[Amit Varma]: question will be, what is the last book you read?

01:24:59.680 --> 01:25:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And for 80% of them, it will be Chetan Bhagat.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And this has and I think my friend said this not with an entirely positive implication,

01:25:07.480 --> 01:25:08.920
[Amit Varma]: but this can cut both ways.

01:25:08.920 --> 01:25:13.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one way, of course, is that these are just people pretending to be readers and

01:25:13.320 --> 01:25:15.800
[Amit Varma]: they're taking the one name that everybody takes.

01:25:15.800 --> 01:25:19.480
[Amit Varma]: But the other way is that, you know, let's not look down on them because they haven't

01:25:19.480 --> 01:25:22.980
[Amit Varma]: been privileged to have the kind of childhoods we have, where we've had access to so many

01:25:22.980 --> 01:25:24.800
[Amit Varma]: books and be able to read so much.

01:25:24.800 --> 01:25:28.440
[Amit Varma]: They want to read and their gateway into the world of reading is Chetan Bhagat, which is

01:25:28.440 --> 01:25:33.080
[Amit Varma]: remarkable, which is also a conventional view of his in the past that he's introduced so

01:25:33.080 --> 01:25:34.520
[Amit Varma]: many new people to reading.

01:25:34.520 --> 01:25:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And that's surely a good thing, because they'll go on to read books by other authors.

01:25:38.880 --> 01:25:41.440
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that has happened or is happening?

01:25:41.440 --> 01:25:45.600
[Guest]: There was a hope at one time that this would happen, that they would read something which

01:25:45.600 --> 01:25:49.280
[Guest]: was easier to access, and then they would go on and climb the next rung to something

01:25:49.280 --> 01:25:51.320
[Guest]: that was more difficult.

01:25:51.320 --> 01:25:55.560
[Guest]: But I don't think there's anything that no data that tells us this is happening.

01:25:55.560 --> 01:26:01.800
[Guest]: What it's telling us is possibly that they read and they said, okay, now we've been there,

01:26:01.800 --> 01:26:02.800
[Guest]: we've done that.

01:26:02.800 --> 01:26:08.000
[Guest]: Now off we go to watch something or do other things that have nothing to do with reading.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:11.220
[Guest]: And no, we're not seeing that ladder.

01:26:11.220 --> 01:26:15.680
[Guest]: So it's not been the most, what is the word I want?

01:26:15.680 --> 01:26:19.080
[Guest]: I mean, it's not like somebody built a foundation on which other people are able to stand up

01:26:19.080 --> 01:26:25.200
[Guest]: and climb and go on, which was a great like that foundation remains a foundation and what

01:26:25.200 --> 01:26:29.400
[Amit Varma]: is to come is still and it's probably important, but we don't really know how yet.

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:35.040
[Guest]: Yeah, no, I also think that this gateway to reading in English is a really important thing,

01:26:35.040 --> 01:26:37.200
[Guest]: because what do kids in most situations do?

01:26:37.200 --> 01:26:41.880
[Guest]: They go to school, they read that school textbook in English, and there's not very much to recommend

01:26:41.880 --> 01:26:44.920
[Guest]: reading further, if you're only reading that.

01:26:44.920 --> 01:26:48.920
[Guest]: So to find something that's entertaining, that appeals to them that relates to their

01:26:48.920 --> 01:26:53.440
[Guest]: worlds and at the same time allows them to feel that they've gone a little further in

01:26:53.440 --> 01:26:55.060
[Guest]: that experience.

01:26:55.060 --> 01:26:58.700
[Guest]: It's remarkable that there just isn't enough material in that space.

01:26:58.700 --> 01:27:01.120
[Guest]: And why isn't there enough material in that space?

01:27:01.120 --> 01:27:07.240
[Guest]: My own feeling is that translations are the space we must look to and build to get that

01:27:07.240 --> 01:27:08.400
[Guest]: experience.

01:27:08.400 --> 01:27:14.320
[Guest]: Because if I am a person reading in Malayalam, and I read my English textbooks, and then

01:27:14.320 --> 01:27:20.000
[Guest]: I go on to read, maybe I may not read the big Malayalam novel even then, because now

01:27:20.000 --> 01:27:22.800
[Guest]: I am a person who has neither language properly, right?

01:27:22.800 --> 01:27:26.280
[Guest]: I don't have a Malayalam well enough, because now I'm going off to live somewhere else.

01:27:26.280 --> 01:27:27.280
[Guest]: And I don't have that.

01:27:27.280 --> 01:27:28.980
[Guest]: I don't have my English well enough.

01:27:28.980 --> 01:27:32.720
[Guest]: And if I have to choose to read, maybe I will choose to read in English, because that is

01:27:32.720 --> 01:27:35.760
[Guest]: the way of aspiration and growth and all of that.

01:27:35.760 --> 01:27:40.560
[Guest]: In which case I might choose to read a novel that applies to me closer, which would be

01:27:40.560 --> 01:27:44.120
[Guest]: the novel which is written in Malayalam in translation English.

01:27:44.120 --> 01:27:49.480
[Guest]: And maybe that gateway would be a powerful gateway to if we allowed ourselves to build

01:27:49.480 --> 01:27:50.600
[Guest]: it up.

01:27:50.600 --> 01:27:55.160
[Guest]: And that would be a very, very meaningful gateway, because that's not a gateway into

01:27:55.160 --> 01:28:01.680
[Guest]: a culture that is alien, or that opens up worlds that we would aspire to.

01:28:01.680 --> 01:28:07.520
[Guest]: It's a world that is very real, where we came from, where our families continue to live,

01:28:07.520 --> 01:28:11.480
[Guest]: and where we hope there is also a future and not just the past.

01:28:11.480 --> 01:28:18.240
[Guest]: So I think it's about a market economy and an editorial and marketing machinery, all

01:28:18.240 --> 01:28:23.560
[Guest]: of which that has to come together and say, can we now focus on shifting the gateway to

01:28:23.560 --> 01:28:30.160
[Guest]: our own languages, and maybe use English as a point there of entry into reading in English,

01:28:30.160 --> 01:28:33.800
[Guest]: and not just leave Chetan Bhagat to be the one person who occupies that space.

01:28:33.800 --> 01:28:36.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's really interesting, because you know, you point out that there is a gap there where

01:28:36.680 --> 01:28:41.360
[Amit Varma]: there aren't enough people at that entry level sort of gateway to English reading thing and

01:28:41.360 --> 01:28:44.960
[Amit Varma]: Chetan Bhagat came and that's great, but there should be more than that.

01:28:44.960 --> 01:28:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, were there publishers like I imagine in the late 90s, there would

01:28:48.080 --> 01:28:52.040
[Amit Varma]: have been many publishers asking themselves, how do I find the next Arundhati Roy?

01:28:52.040 --> 01:28:55.800
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, were there many publishers saying, how do I find the next Chetan Bhagat?

01:28:55.800 --> 01:29:01.400
[Amit Varma]: Of course, and how much of that question is then saying that just as Chetan Bhagat was

01:29:01.400 --> 01:29:05.800
[Amit Varma]: a manufacturer entity in the sense that he manufactured himself, he came with a PowerPoint

01:29:05.800 --> 01:29:07.800
[Amit Varma]: of how I should promote this.

01:29:07.800 --> 01:29:12.520
[Amit Varma]: How much was there that sense that the next Chetan Bhagat also has to be manufactured

01:29:12.520 --> 01:29:13.520
[Amit Varma]: perhaps by us?

01:29:13.520 --> 01:29:16.480
[Amit Varma]: Like, is this a quest that publishers sort of went down?

01:29:16.480 --> 01:29:20.920
[Guest]: I think one of a brilliant example of that building on Chetan Bhagat is the Srishti publishing

01:29:20.920 --> 01:29:21.920
[Guest]: program.

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:28.680
[Guest]: I think what they did was to say, let's create a mass market entity and every book we publish

01:29:28.680 --> 01:29:30.480
[Guest]: will go into that.

01:29:30.480 --> 01:29:34.060
[Guest]: And much like say a Mills and Boone brand did one time, you knew what you were getting

01:29:34.060 --> 01:29:35.680
[Guest]: when you saw that brand, right?

01:29:35.680 --> 01:29:39.080
[Guest]: Which is the thing that the large publishing houses have lost out on.

01:29:39.080 --> 01:29:42.960
[Guest]: Now if you pick up a book from a major publishing house, you will recognize the logo and you

01:29:42.960 --> 01:29:44.680
[Guest]: ascribe to it certain qualities.

01:29:44.680 --> 01:29:46.520
[Guest]: You will say, oh, this will be a well edited book.

01:29:46.520 --> 01:29:47.520
[Guest]: This will be error free.

01:29:47.520 --> 01:29:49.140
[Guest]: Perhaps this will be well packaged.

01:29:49.140 --> 01:29:53.600
[Guest]: One assumes that there is a certain requirement for this book to exist.

01:29:53.600 --> 01:29:54.880
[Guest]: All of that is true.

01:29:54.880 --> 01:29:59.460
[Guest]: But there is no guarantee of what the content will be like and whether there is any similarity

01:29:59.460 --> 01:30:02.960
[Guest]: to something else that that publishing house did because each one is publishing so many

01:30:02.960 --> 01:30:04.880
[Guest]: kinds of books.

01:30:04.880 --> 01:30:09.760
[Guest]: But Srishti created a brand that said, whatever you pick from this list, you know exactly

01:30:09.760 --> 01:30:10.760
[Guest]: what you're going to get.

01:30:10.760 --> 01:30:15.720
[Guest]: And it's going to be a novel that will entertain you or which will be easy to read, which you

01:30:15.720 --> 01:30:17.280
[Guest]: will enjoy.

01:30:17.280 --> 01:30:19.400
[Guest]: And so pick just the brand.

01:30:19.400 --> 01:30:22.400
[Guest]: Don't pick necessarily the writer or the book.

01:30:22.400 --> 01:30:26.160
[Guest]: And I don't think anybody else has actually done that in the English language space.

01:30:26.160 --> 01:30:27.520
[Guest]: Were they sort of successful?

01:30:27.520 --> 01:30:29.680
[Guest]: I think they were very successful.

01:30:29.680 --> 01:30:34.840
[Guest]: The difficulty with that is that when a small publishing house cannot back the writer in

01:30:34.840 --> 01:30:38.680
[Guest]: terms of the aggressive marketing that they're often looking for, then they migrate to other

01:30:38.680 --> 01:30:41.240
[Guest]: publishing houses that offer them more money.

01:30:41.240 --> 01:30:42.720
[Guest]: And so they go on.

01:30:42.720 --> 01:30:48.800
[Guest]: But I think even now, any book that Srishti does will find space in certain stores and

01:30:48.800 --> 01:30:51.040
[Guest]: certain and people will pick them up and walk away.

01:30:51.040 --> 01:30:56.320
[Guest]: I remember when I was in HarperCollins a few years in my colleague who was the sales person

01:30:56.320 --> 01:31:00.320
[Guest]: in the north, he came to me and he said, ma'am, you have to publish books like this, like

01:31:00.320 --> 01:31:01.680
[Guest]: this is what sells.

01:31:01.680 --> 01:31:06.040
[Guest]: I went to Lucknow and they told me that this bookshelf that every now and then they have

01:31:06.040 --> 01:31:10.640
[Guest]: to replenish like 25 copies of each book because people just walk in and look at it and they

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:11.800
[Guest]: just buy it and walk out.

01:31:11.800 --> 01:31:14.280
[Guest]: They don't want to know who the writer is.

01:31:14.280 --> 01:31:20.720
[Guest]: So the thing about publishing is obviously that we are not able to brand ourselves as

01:31:20.720 --> 01:31:21.720
[Guest]: publishers.

01:31:21.720 --> 01:31:22.720
[Guest]: We often have to brand the writer.

01:31:22.720 --> 01:31:24.320
[Guest]: The writer is the brand.

01:31:24.320 --> 01:31:29.880
[Guest]: So if you're publishing a writer today who's not published before, you have to start building

01:31:29.880 --> 01:31:32.240
[Guest]: that brand from scratch for that writer.

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:34.480
[Guest]: And identity has to be built around them.

01:31:34.480 --> 01:31:38.560
[Guest]: Then the next time they write a book, if they choose to write in the same genre, you have

01:31:38.560 --> 01:31:42.640
[Guest]: ease of marketing, but they might choose to write a completely different novel, especially

01:31:42.640 --> 01:31:43.640
[Guest]: literary writers.

01:31:43.640 --> 01:31:45.840
[Guest]: They write a completely different thing the next time.

01:31:45.840 --> 01:31:48.600
[Guest]: And then you have to start all over again, building that brand.

01:31:48.600 --> 01:31:54.840
[Guest]: So each day, each writer, each book is a different proposition altogether.

01:31:54.840 --> 01:31:59.920
[Guest]: Whereas if you have a brand which says this is what I am very clearly, then you don't

01:31:59.920 --> 01:32:03.720
[Guest]: have to worry about who the writer is, how well known they are, what social media profiles

01:32:03.720 --> 01:32:04.720
[Guest]: they have.

01:32:04.720 --> 01:32:12.080
[Guest]: You are giving the brand the identity, and that is so much easier to market as a whole.

01:32:12.080 --> 01:32:18.180
[Guest]: But at the moment, all of us are struggling with this fact of expansion of multiple categories

01:32:18.180 --> 01:32:19.960
[Guest]: within each publishing house.

01:32:19.960 --> 01:32:22.320
[Guest]: And how on earth are we to say what are we?

01:32:22.320 --> 01:32:23.480
[Guest]: How do we identify ourselves?

01:32:23.480 --> 01:32:26.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I guess you could have an imprint which does only that.

01:32:26.840 --> 01:32:27.840
[Guest]: Right.

01:32:27.840 --> 01:32:28.840
[Guest]: So we do imprints.

01:32:28.840 --> 01:32:33.480
[Guest]: So for instance, I started up this imprint with a colleague, which is called Context.

01:32:33.480 --> 01:32:35.560
[Guest]: So Ajita and I do that at Westland.

01:32:35.560 --> 01:32:40.880
[Guest]: And we think of context as this literary imprint, as an imprint that does very politically engaged

01:32:40.880 --> 01:32:46.140
[Guest]: content in fiction and nonfiction, that hopefully will do some experimental work as well, etc.

01:32:46.140 --> 01:32:47.640
[Guest]: So we identify ourselves like that.

01:32:47.640 --> 01:32:49.760
[Guest]: And we try and build a list like that.

01:32:49.760 --> 01:32:54.120
[Guest]: Then we have something called Westland Sport, which is clearly a sport publishing imprint.

01:32:54.120 --> 01:32:56.080
[Guest]: We'll have a business imprint next year.

01:32:56.080 --> 01:32:58.320
[Guest]: So things like that you can do, right?

01:32:58.320 --> 01:33:01.240
[Guest]: So then people go into a store and they will see it and they will say, OK, this is a business

01:33:01.240 --> 01:33:02.240
[Guest]: imprint.

01:33:02.240 --> 01:33:04.600
[Guest]: I don't know what to get from here.

01:33:04.600 --> 01:33:13.240
[Guest]: But when you have sort of intangibles, where you have a novel that is just a great read,

01:33:13.240 --> 01:33:18.000
[Guest]: a brand is difficult to sustain on books like that.

01:33:18.000 --> 01:33:20.920
[Guest]: And yet those are the books that you really wish more people would read, because they

01:33:20.920 --> 01:33:24.040
[Guest]: are the books that you want to curl up with on a summer afternoon and read.

01:33:24.040 --> 01:33:25.960
[Guest]: But how on earth do you brand that then?

01:33:25.960 --> 01:33:30.320
[Guest]: There you have to brand the writer so that people know if a Bridget Jones is written

01:33:30.320 --> 01:33:34.960
[Guest]: by Helen Fielding, then anything she writes, hopefully, will be as entertaining and as

01:33:34.960 --> 01:33:35.960
[Guest]: smart as that.

01:33:35.960 --> 01:33:37.240
[Guest]: So I'll walk off with it.

01:33:37.240 --> 01:33:42.360
[Guest]: So each time a publicist works on a book, I think they have to work on the content of

01:33:42.360 --> 01:33:45.240
[Guest]: the book, and they have to build the writer.

01:33:45.240 --> 01:33:48.040
[Guest]: So it's extremely complicated.

01:33:48.040 --> 01:33:52.160
[Guest]: Bringing that book to the reader is each time a challenging task.

01:33:52.160 --> 01:33:56.200
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, just as an aside for the past few months, you guys have been sending me

01:33:56.200 --> 01:33:57.200
[Amit Varma]: books from context.

01:33:57.200 --> 01:34:01.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it's actually got that very clear identity in my mind, because from what

01:34:01.800 --> 01:34:04.840
[Amit Varma]: I have seen of the context books, some of which have featured on the show, and I've

01:34:04.840 --> 01:34:08.600
[Amit Varma]: really enjoyed is that they all engage with contemporary India.

01:34:08.600 --> 01:34:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which is why that, you know, even the branding of context seems to me to be sort

01:34:14.320 --> 01:34:15.320
[Amit Varma]: of very spot on.

01:34:15.320 --> 01:34:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, you were talking about sort of the different categories that you have to deal with within

01:34:20.000 --> 01:34:21.440
[Amit Varma]: a publishing house.

01:34:21.440 --> 01:34:25.680
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of this is something that's again evolved during your time in publishing.

01:34:25.680 --> 01:34:30.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've sort of, you know, through the 2000s, and you had all these new categories

01:34:30.400 --> 01:34:34.360
[Unknown]: like nonfiction, like the sort of historical writing that William Dalrymple and Ram Guha

01:34:34.360 --> 01:34:39.680
[Amit Varma]: do sort of also explored in these new appetites kind of come up.

01:34:39.680 --> 01:34:46.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about your process of discovery of these new appetites as a publisher.

01:34:46.440 --> 01:34:53.080
[Guest]: I think one of the instances that actually was a learning for me and a category learning

01:34:53.080 --> 01:34:58.360
[Guest]: for ourselves as publishers was when we published Sarnath Banerjee's first graphic novel.

01:34:58.360 --> 01:35:03.240
[Guest]: Because I remember that when that was first published, there was no graphic novel publishing.

01:35:03.240 --> 01:35:05.880
[Guest]: Or Ajit Sen's book was the first that came out.

01:35:05.880 --> 01:35:10.920
[Guest]: But that was not something that went out into sort of trade so much.

01:35:10.920 --> 01:35:13.740
[Guest]: So there it was like saying, what on earth is this work?

01:35:13.740 --> 01:35:14.740
[Guest]: What is this form?

01:35:14.740 --> 01:35:16.400
[Guest]: What is this meant to be?

01:35:16.400 --> 01:35:19.960
[Guest]: And how on earth are we going to sell it or get people to receive it?

01:35:19.960 --> 01:35:25.520
[Guest]: Similarly, I think there have been points at which we've said, okay, so if you're doing

01:35:25.520 --> 01:35:31.920
[Guest]: say an Anuja Chauhan, when Zoya Factor first came out, I had a colleague Yogesh in Harper,

01:35:31.920 --> 01:35:36.320
[Guest]: who was very aggressive about, let's sell it, he said, let's, let's put 20,000 copies

01:35:36.320 --> 01:35:37.320
[Guest]: out.

01:35:37.320 --> 01:35:42.200
[Guest]: And I still remember, I think it was Anant who was then at Penguin and now in Harper,

01:35:42.200 --> 01:35:46.960
[Guest]: who called me and said, you're doing a novel, which is like 20,000 print run.

01:35:46.960 --> 01:35:50.000
[Guest]: I'm not sure he was talking about Anuja or he was talking about another writer called

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:52.520
[Guest]: Sam Born, who also we'd put out very aggressively.

01:35:52.520 --> 01:35:54.480
[Guest]: And we were like, yeah, we did that.

01:35:54.480 --> 01:35:57.500
[Guest]: And it must have been foolhardy when you look back at it.

01:35:57.500 --> 01:35:58.500
[Guest]: But it worked.

01:35:58.500 --> 01:35:59.880
[Guest]: I mean, Anuja is a phenomenon.

01:35:59.880 --> 01:36:02.280
[Guest]: And sometimes I think you get lucky.

01:36:02.280 --> 01:36:08.040
[Guest]: You bring out a book that is in a category that doesn't quite exist, and you get the

01:36:08.040 --> 01:36:10.040
[Guest]: right person at the right time.

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:12.680
[Guest]: And then you can like really build on it.

01:36:12.680 --> 01:36:18.680
[Guest]: But it doesn't always work, because you might also then find yourself saying, okay, the

01:36:18.680 --> 01:36:23.720
[Guest]: next big thing is a historical fiction, based on the fact that the big historical novel,

01:36:23.720 --> 01:36:26.440
[Guest]: the big historical romance is really big in the West.

01:36:26.440 --> 01:36:29.120
[Guest]: But you will find that there are a few writers who do really well.

01:36:29.120 --> 01:36:35.080
[Guest]: I remember publishing Indu Sundaresan, whose Feast of Roses and that whole Noor Jahan,

01:36:35.080 --> 01:36:41.600
[Guest]: Mughal world of big glamorous court and romance and so on, did really well, continues to be

01:36:41.600 --> 01:36:45.520
[Guest]: in print, like what, 15 years after they were first published.

01:36:45.520 --> 01:36:51.960
[Guest]: But it's taken 15 years after that for this sudden resurgence of writing around the Mughals

01:36:51.960 --> 01:36:54.640
[Guest]: and popular history and so on.

01:36:54.640 --> 01:36:56.740
[Guest]: There was very little at that time.

01:36:56.740 --> 01:36:59.760
[Guest]: So one didn't think this time would come either.

01:36:59.760 --> 01:37:03.720
[Guest]: But at that point, it made sense to publish one writer who was doing that.

01:37:03.720 --> 01:37:10.360
[Guest]: So I think the categories have evolved with more people discovering that their own tastes

01:37:10.360 --> 01:37:12.640
[Guest]: match with, say, one writer somehow.

01:37:12.640 --> 01:37:17.800
[Guest]: It's like Vikram Seth, when A Suitable Boy came out, a lot of people suddenly said, oh,

01:37:17.800 --> 01:37:19.320
[Guest]: this is exactly what I want to read.

01:37:19.320 --> 01:37:21.080
[Guest]: And I didn't know I wanted to read this.

01:37:21.080 --> 01:37:23.520
[Guest]: I think that's the same sort of discovery for an editor.

01:37:23.520 --> 01:37:27.880
[Guest]: When I read Serious Men, the manuscript by Manu Joseph first, it was like, oh, I always

01:37:27.880 --> 01:37:34.400
[Guest]: wanted to read a really well written novel set so deeply, you know, in our own world.

01:37:34.400 --> 01:37:36.720
[Guest]: And I haven't read something like this for a long time.

01:37:36.720 --> 01:37:42.040
[Guest]: And when you feel that sense of discovery and excitement, you know, it will be shared.

01:37:42.040 --> 01:37:47.160
[Guest]: And it's a matter of just finding a way to reach those people who will share that excitement.

01:37:47.160 --> 01:37:53.920
[Guest]: So yeah, over the years, I suppose, from poetry to graphic to literary fiction to young adult

01:37:53.920 --> 01:37:57.280
[Guest]: writing, which again, is a very small category.

01:37:57.280 --> 01:37:59.840
[Guest]: But occasionally you have that one spurt or one thing.

01:37:59.840 --> 01:38:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I didn't know it existed in India.

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:06.000
[Guest]: You know, the thing is, it exists for books that are coming in from elsewhere.

01:38:06.000 --> 01:38:09.480
[Guest]: So everyone will read a Harry Potter and a Rick Riordan and all of that.

01:38:09.480 --> 01:38:11.720
[Guest]: But we still to find that breakthrough here.

01:38:11.720 --> 01:38:15.920
[Guest]: So till a suitable boy came along, nobody thought that big literary novel would have

01:38:15.920 --> 01:38:18.920
[Guest]: a great audience in India, but it suddenly found that it had.

01:38:18.920 --> 01:38:24.280
[Guest]: Similarly, I'm like waiting for that young adult novel that will just grab everybody

01:38:24.280 --> 01:38:27.400
[Guest]: and say, oh, and opens up the market.

01:38:27.400 --> 01:38:34.440
[Guest]: That is one category that has not found anything yet that is truly revolutionized the numbers.

01:38:34.440 --> 01:38:38.680
[Amit Varma]: And how much of writerly success like as a publisher, you know, whenever you publish,

01:38:38.680 --> 01:38:41.440
[Amit Varma]: you always have a sense that these are the guys I think will do well.

01:38:41.440 --> 01:38:43.840
[Amit Varma]: And these are the guys who may not do so well.

01:38:43.840 --> 01:38:47.160
[Amit Varma]: And how much does reality conform to that?

01:38:47.160 --> 01:38:53.240
[Amit Varma]: And to what extent does the success of writers to what is the role that luck plays just happening

01:38:53.240 --> 01:38:56.320
[Amit Varma]: to take off and hit the zeitgeist at the right time?

01:38:56.320 --> 01:38:58.000
[Guest]: I think luck has a lot to do with that.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:03.240
[Guest]: I remember when I joined Harper, this was the time when I talked about Anuja, there

01:39:03.240 --> 01:39:06.440
[Guest]: was another writer called Advaita Akala, whose first book came out.

01:39:06.440 --> 01:39:13.160
[Guest]: There was Karan Bajaj, whose novel that came out.

01:39:13.160 --> 01:39:17.920
[Guest]: And we were hitting 20 to 30 to 40,000 copies of those books because the time was just right.

01:39:17.920 --> 01:39:20.240
[Guest]: Amitabh Bagchi's first novel Above Average.

01:39:20.240 --> 01:39:23.520
[Guest]: I remember that first year it did some 25,000 copies.

01:39:23.520 --> 01:39:27.000
[Guest]: And all of this was completely out of the blue, but the time was right.

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:28.480
[Guest]: The numbers were right.

01:39:28.480 --> 01:39:33.920
[Guest]: And everyone wanted to read that next step up on the commercial novel, you know, and

01:39:33.920 --> 01:39:35.880
[Guest]: I think a lot of it has to do with luck.

01:39:35.880 --> 01:39:37.480
[Guest]: It has to do with finding that.

01:39:37.480 --> 01:39:40.920
[Guest]: And then you'll find that you've done brilliant books, which everyone thought was like the

01:39:40.920 --> 01:39:45.840
[Guest]: best in the genre, which a few hundred people read or a couple of thousand people read,

01:39:45.840 --> 01:39:50.440
[Guest]: were greatly reviewed, beautifully reviewed, but they just did not sell beyond that.

01:39:50.440 --> 01:39:54.360
[Amit Varma]: Can you name some books which are favorites of yours, which you wish had done much better?

01:39:54.360 --> 01:39:59.920
[Guest]: I can tell you one book that we published last year, which was Revati Lal's Anatomy

01:39:59.920 --> 01:40:06.840
[Guest]: of Hate, which I think is a striking instance of a book that has everything to recommend

01:40:06.840 --> 01:40:07.840
[Guest]: it.

01:40:07.840 --> 01:40:16.960
[Guest]: Real politic, heart, new ideas, all written in a way that just goes beyond what you have

01:40:16.960 --> 01:40:18.760
[Guest]: in that genre at the moment.

01:40:18.760 --> 01:40:20.080
[Guest]: And of course, it was wonderfully reviewed.

01:40:20.080 --> 01:40:23.720
[Guest]: Recently, Biblio put it on their outstanding books for the year and all of that.

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:27.520
[Guest]: But why are the readers not backing it in the way that it should?

01:40:27.520 --> 01:40:28.880
[Guest]: You know, it's a mystery.

01:40:28.880 --> 01:40:29.880
[Guest]: Why something?

01:40:29.880 --> 01:40:33.120
[Guest]: I know that after a certain point, it's also about the profile of the writer.

01:40:33.120 --> 01:40:36.240
[Guest]: Like after a certain point, anything that a certain writer writes, we get that first

01:40:36.240 --> 01:40:37.240
[Guest]: pickup.

01:40:37.240 --> 01:40:39.080
[Guest]: The first 10,000, 20,000 copies will move.

01:40:39.080 --> 01:40:40.220
[Guest]: We know that.

01:40:40.220 --> 01:40:44.240
[Guest]: But why is there a reluctance to back unknowns?

01:40:44.240 --> 01:40:49.040
[Guest]: Why is there not even with marketing machinery behind it, even with reviewers backing it?

01:40:49.040 --> 01:40:53.440
[Guest]: There's something about luck there that that seems to suggest that it's beyond you.

01:40:53.440 --> 01:40:55.920
[Guest]: And yet I'm convinced that books like that will last.

01:40:55.920 --> 01:41:02.320
[Guest]: We'll go on to get into citations phases, we'll go into reading in universities, and

01:41:02.320 --> 01:41:05.600
[Guest]: we'll find a different way to remain alive and relevant.

01:41:05.600 --> 01:41:07.600
[Guest]: This may be influence future writers.

01:41:07.600 --> 01:41:08.600
[Guest]: That's right.

01:41:08.600 --> 01:41:09.960
[Guest]: That means all of that could happen.

01:41:09.960 --> 01:41:15.720
[Guest]: But here and now you wish it had that other hit of luck that would take it further.

01:41:15.720 --> 01:41:19.320
[Amit Varma]: No, and Revati's book, which I enjoyed a lot is of course an intensely political book,

01:41:19.320 --> 01:41:24.600
[Amit Varma]: which also brings me to a question which I think, especially in the last few years, publishers

01:41:24.600 --> 01:41:30.440
[Amit Varma]: must have had to grapple with, which is the pressures of politics and the temptation to

01:41:30.440 --> 01:41:33.320
[Amit Varma]: self censor something so you do not get in trouble.

01:41:33.320 --> 01:41:37.440
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote from a piece you wrote for Caravan a few years ago.

01:41:37.440 --> 01:41:42.560
[Amit Varma]: Quote, when the system seems to connive with the mob to prevent free expression and dissemination

01:41:42.560 --> 01:41:44.720
[Amit Varma]: of content, what is a publisher to do?

01:41:44.720 --> 01:41:49.400
[Amit Varma]: The easy thing would be to follow the letter of the law and not test the ideals, if one

01:41:49.400 --> 01:41:53.400
[Amit Varma]: could call them that, or patience of any part of society.

01:41:53.400 --> 01:41:57.600
[Amit Varma]: An insider's account of life inside an ashram in southern India, dangerous.

01:41:57.600 --> 01:42:02.600
[Amit Varma]: A novel that dramatizes caste conflict in Uttar Pradesh based on a real incident, potentially

01:42:02.600 --> 01:42:03.600
[Amit Varma]: provocative.

01:42:03.600 --> 01:42:08.280
[Amit Varma]: A study of the violence implicit in religious conversion in different parts of India, best

01:42:08.280 --> 01:42:09.280
[Amit Varma]: avoided.

01:42:09.280 --> 01:42:13.840
[Amit Varma]: An erotic fantasy that stars a young Muslim girl, a definite cause of anxiety.

01:42:13.840 --> 01:42:19.240
[Amit Varma]: And so it could go on a seemingly endless list of dangerous subjects and by extension,

01:42:19.240 --> 01:42:21.200
[Amit Varma]: unmarketable writers.

01:42:21.200 --> 01:42:25.360
[Amit Varma]: The other way to respond would be to take the route further north, instead of throwing

01:42:25.360 --> 01:42:30.880
[Amit Varma]: water on the wood, even before the flame is lit, to sit down and plan the fire.

01:42:30.880 --> 01:42:33.680
[Amit Varma]: Stop good, which beautiful, very moving words.

01:42:33.680 --> 01:42:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Explain what you mean by sitting down and planning the fire.

01:42:36.920 --> 01:42:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, what is your approach?

01:42:38.240 --> 01:42:43.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you have not shied away from publishing books that could be controversial.

01:42:43.320 --> 01:42:44.320
[Amit Varma]: What is your approach then?

01:42:44.320 --> 01:42:45.840
[Guest]: How do you deal with this?

01:42:45.840 --> 01:42:50.040
[Guest]: I think I have one clear rule, which is that you do not break the law.

01:42:50.040 --> 01:42:57.120
[Guest]: That as long as what you've got in that work is not defamatory, not libelous, not doing

01:42:57.120 --> 01:43:01.500
[Guest]: something that the law says is not acceptable.

01:43:01.500 --> 01:43:03.000
[Amit Varma]: That is the one clear line to draw.

01:43:03.000 --> 01:43:05.200
[Guest]: But the law is also so open to interpretation, right?

01:43:05.200 --> 01:43:06.200
[Guest]: Correct.

01:43:06.200 --> 01:43:10.840
[Guest]: So, your legal team will help you interpret it in the way that it should be, hopefully.

01:43:10.840 --> 01:43:16.480
[Guest]: And I think we have some very bright PR lawyers and we have an intensely sensible team in

01:43:16.480 --> 01:43:20.520
[Guest]: house which shows us what's all right and what's not.

01:43:20.520 --> 01:43:25.880
[Guest]: But I also think I honestly don't give a fig about people being offended in this way that

01:43:25.880 --> 01:43:30.100
[Guest]: this nebulous can be interpreted in any way, offense.

01:43:30.100 --> 01:43:35.120
[Guest]: You know, we've had this recent instance of that pug, I mean, the turban tying book.

01:43:35.120 --> 01:43:36.120
[Unknown]: Have you read about that?

01:43:36.120 --> 01:43:37.120
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:43:37.120 --> 01:43:41.120
[Guest]: I mean, people backed the book from the market and so on.

01:43:41.120 --> 01:43:43.400
[Guest]: And I think that's a real shame.

01:43:43.400 --> 01:43:45.280
[Guest]: I mean, forget self-censorship.

01:43:45.280 --> 01:43:53.120
[Guest]: If you can't make fun of yourself, if you can't have fun with things around you, question

01:43:53.120 --> 01:43:57.960
[Guest]: them all the time, then we're just sliding into a space where you only walk the straight

01:43:57.960 --> 01:43:59.100
[Guest]: line.

01:43:59.100 --> 01:44:01.760
[Guest]: And what does that bring to anyone anyway?

01:44:01.760 --> 01:44:06.960
[Guest]: As long as you have enough people supporting you in taking that step which says, I've broken

01:44:06.960 --> 01:44:12.160
[Guest]: no law, but I am going to ask the questions through my author or whoever is writing that

01:44:12.160 --> 01:44:15.360
[Guest]: book that need to be asked.

01:44:15.360 --> 01:44:17.520
[Guest]: Do it because that's the only reason to be.

01:44:17.520 --> 01:44:23.240
[Guest]: I mean, the older you get in the profession, the more you have to ask yourself, why are

01:44:23.240 --> 01:44:24.840
[Guest]: you doing what you're doing?

01:44:24.840 --> 01:44:25.840
[Guest]: Right.

01:44:25.840 --> 01:44:31.020
[Guest]: If you're doing this to be genuinely engaged with what matters around you.

01:44:31.020 --> 01:44:41.280
[Guest]: And I do think that since 2014, I have particularly felt much more troubled and much more intent

01:44:41.280 --> 01:44:46.560
[Guest]: on trying to do whatever little bit one can to keep the conversation alive about the things

01:44:46.560 --> 01:44:48.120
[Guest]: that matter to me.

01:44:48.120 --> 01:44:53.360
[Guest]: Then the only route open to me is to publish books that I care about in that space and

01:44:53.360 --> 01:44:56.680
[Guest]: to find writers who write about things that matter.

01:44:56.680 --> 01:45:03.440
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that if I see a good book, well argued and written well, from another

01:45:03.440 --> 01:45:07.380
[Guest]: political point of view, that does not have a place either.

01:45:07.380 --> 01:45:08.560
[Guest]: It does.

01:45:08.560 --> 01:45:13.840
[Guest]: But I must admit, I bring a different heart and a different commitment to the books that

01:45:13.840 --> 01:45:20.120
[Guest]: talk about democracy and the republic and India in ways that I hold dear to myself.

01:45:20.120 --> 01:45:25.880
[Guest]: And thankfully, if you can find the right writers and get the right books, then there

01:45:25.880 --> 01:45:30.400
[Guest]: are enough readers to sustain that as a saleable proposition.

01:45:30.400 --> 01:45:33.360
[Guest]: So it's not bad business either.

01:45:33.360 --> 01:45:37.600
[Guest]: Of course, there are this point of view of diversity, for instance, there are people

01:45:37.600 --> 01:45:40.600
[Guest]: in a publishing house will have very different political points of view.

01:45:40.600 --> 01:45:44.840
[Guest]: And you can't as a publisher say, no, no, no, we will only publish what I believe in.

01:45:44.840 --> 01:45:49.880
[Guest]: So obviously, there is always space to publish right, left, center, whatever.

01:45:49.880 --> 01:45:51.860
[Guest]: But that is the sheer beauty of it, right?

01:45:51.860 --> 01:45:56.400
[Guest]: As many readers and as many points of view as there are, the more you can put out, because

01:45:56.400 --> 01:46:02.040
[Guest]: the most important thing is also, I think, to understand what the other side is saying

01:46:02.040 --> 01:46:06.760
[Guest]: and to engage with it intelligently, rather than to dismiss it as something not to be

01:46:06.760 --> 01:46:08.200
[Guest]: talked about at all.

01:46:08.200 --> 01:46:09.800
[Guest]: That is a grave mistake.

01:46:09.800 --> 01:46:15.120
[Guest]: And which is why I want to see more publishing, for instance, on the right by people who believe

01:46:15.120 --> 01:46:20.680
[Guest]: in that worldview, because I want to understand what it is before I can knock it down.

01:46:20.680 --> 01:46:24.760
[Amit Varma]: No, and that also enriches the discourse, if you can work with a writer whose views

01:46:24.760 --> 01:46:28.840
[Amit Varma]: you may not agree with, but you help him get the best version of his views.

01:46:28.840 --> 01:46:32.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what kind of strikes me here is and I'm just looking at sort of journalism

01:46:32.280 --> 01:46:33.560
[Amit Varma]: as an analog.

01:46:33.560 --> 01:46:39.680
[Amit Varma]: And what one sees in journalism is that more and more you see the really big sort of entities

01:46:39.680 --> 01:46:44.600
[Amit Varma]: like the major mainstream newspapers and so on, play it safe, self censor when they feel

01:46:44.600 --> 01:46:49.640
[Amit Varma]: like and one understands why that is because they have business imperatives that go beyond

01:46:49.640 --> 01:46:51.080
[Amit Varma]: the newspaper business.

01:46:51.080 --> 01:46:55.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, they are in all other kinds of businesses, a government can put pressure, threaten raids,

01:46:55.480 --> 01:46:58.760
[Amit Varma]: ask for their tax returns again, and so on and so forth.

01:46:58.760 --> 01:47:00.680
[Amit Varma]: There are a million ways of putting pressure.

01:47:00.680 --> 01:47:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And what you see is a bunch of young publications, which are bravely fighting the good fight

01:47:04.680 --> 01:47:08.680
[Amit Varma]: people like scroll wire, alt news, whatever, we know who they are.

01:47:08.680 --> 01:47:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And in publishing, on the other hand, the standard you have taken is that no, it is

01:47:13.160 --> 01:47:17.840
[Amit Varma]: a big people who should fight because we have the legal resources to actually fight this

01:47:17.840 --> 01:47:18.840
[Amit Varma]: fight.

01:47:18.840 --> 01:47:19.840
[Amit Varma]: And we are doing the right thing.

01:47:19.840 --> 01:47:20.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:47:20.840 --> 01:47:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me as a worry that, you know, it's great that you should say that, but you're

01:47:25.120 --> 01:47:29.920
[Amit Varma]: an individual and a lot of this is coming from personal conviction.

01:47:29.920 --> 01:47:35.600
[Amit Varma]: But is this kind of approach something that can survive in the system beyond individuals

01:47:35.600 --> 01:47:36.720
[Guest]: like yourself?

01:47:36.720 --> 01:47:38.080
[Guest]: I think it can.

01:47:38.080 --> 01:47:44.680
[Guest]: And I think it will, because, for one thing, the pressures are not the same, especially

01:47:44.680 --> 01:47:46.280
[Guest]: within English language publishing, right?

01:47:46.280 --> 01:47:51.320
[Guest]: I don't think this could be said of publishing in Hindi, for instance, or in other languages,

01:47:51.320 --> 01:47:56.800
[Guest]: where the voter is very close to that language and to that culture.

01:47:56.800 --> 01:48:02.800
[Guest]: Whereas I think the establishment does not care as much about the English language publishing

01:48:02.800 --> 01:48:08.640
[Guest]: space, because they also know that in some ways, it is still an echo chamber.

01:48:08.640 --> 01:48:13.240
[Guest]: And it is not going to drastically change the way people think much as we'd like to

01:48:13.240 --> 01:48:15.040
[Guest]: think that we can achieve that.

01:48:15.040 --> 01:48:20.320
[Guest]: I think we are often talking to converts who are already thinking along the way we lines

01:48:20.320 --> 01:48:21.320
[Guest]: we are.

01:48:21.320 --> 01:48:23.600
[Guest]: So it's a kind of revalidation.

01:48:23.600 --> 01:48:27.440
[Guest]: Sometimes it's like talking to yourself over and over again, which is also important to

01:48:27.440 --> 01:48:28.440
[Guest]: do.

01:48:28.440 --> 01:48:34.760
[Guest]: But the day it becomes a matter of urgency that this conversation of a book with a reader

01:48:34.760 --> 01:48:41.520
[Guest]: in the English language will actually change a vote or turn a vote or make constituencies

01:48:41.520 --> 01:48:46.040
[Guest]: of those people, I think that is the day we will face genuine pressure.

01:48:46.040 --> 01:48:50.680
[Guest]: At the moment, that pressure is not so big that we can't resist.

01:48:50.680 --> 01:48:56.680
[Guest]: It just takes a strong legal team, it takes some public support, and you can get past

01:48:56.680 --> 01:48:57.680
[Guest]: it.

01:48:57.680 --> 01:49:04.240
[Guest]: But when it comes to religion, then obviously there are problems because sometimes it's

01:49:04.240 --> 01:49:08.320
[Guest]: simply a matter of you're saying, even if I'm within a publishing house that can protect

01:49:08.320 --> 01:49:11.360
[Guest]: me, there are other people in that publishing house.

01:49:11.360 --> 01:49:15.840
[Guest]: And stones can be thrown at anyone and somebody can be taken off to jail as representative

01:49:15.840 --> 01:49:19.880
[Guest]: of that publishing house who had nothing to do with the choice I make as an individual.

01:49:19.880 --> 01:49:23.700
[Guest]: And that is an unfair passing on of responsibility.

01:49:23.700 --> 01:49:27.960
[Guest]: So there will be times when you have to take the call and say, well, this is done, but

01:49:27.960 --> 01:49:32.000
[Guest]: maybe we just can't live up to it beyond a point.

01:49:32.000 --> 01:49:35.160
[Guest]: And so we have to succumb to the reality of it.

01:49:35.160 --> 01:49:39.840
[Guest]: Thankfully, in my own experience, that hasn't come to be, there has been no such thing,

01:49:39.840 --> 01:49:41.040
[Guest]: but I see it around me.

01:49:41.040 --> 01:49:45.880
[Guest]: I see publishers and editors who've had to go through that experience, and it's very

01:49:45.880 --> 01:49:46.880
[Guest]: difficult.

01:49:46.880 --> 01:49:52.840
[Guest]: So far from sitting in judgment on anyone who has to either self-censor or pull back

01:49:52.840 --> 01:49:57.800
[Guest]: books or whatever, I'd say the problem here is that we don't have enough support when

01:49:57.800 --> 01:49:58.800
[Guest]: these things happen.

01:49:58.800 --> 01:50:01.400
[Guest]: People don't care enough to step out and fight that battle.

01:50:01.400 --> 01:50:06.320
[Guest]: I mean, when Perumal Murugan said, I'm dead as a writer, it took a court to say, do what

01:50:06.320 --> 01:50:09.480
[Guest]: you do best, which is right, and go back and do it.

01:50:09.480 --> 01:50:14.440
[Guest]: And he did it, right, and he's now one of our best known writers and the best writers

01:50:14.440 --> 01:50:15.720
[Guest]: we have.

01:50:15.720 --> 01:50:17.720
[Guest]: But there was support for him.

01:50:17.720 --> 01:50:20.600
[Guest]: There were people who went out and said, this is an important battle to fight.

01:50:20.600 --> 01:50:25.640
[Guest]: His publisher, Kannan Sundaram Kalachuvuda, stood by him, and they went to court with

01:50:25.640 --> 01:50:26.640
[Guest]: him.

01:50:26.640 --> 01:50:32.540
[Guest]: If it takes a few individuals to back publishing in a certain way, it also takes only a few

01:50:32.540 --> 01:50:37.200
[Guest]: individuals to fight the battles that matter, as long as they are supported enough by the

01:50:37.200 --> 01:50:38.600
[Guest]: larger community.

01:50:38.600 --> 01:50:43.080
[Guest]: And I think if we don't see the necessity for that in this time, we're never going to

01:50:43.080 --> 01:50:46.000
[Guest]: see it again, because we're not going to have the freedom to see it again.

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:47.800
[Guest]: So we'd better stand together.

01:50:47.800 --> 01:50:49.420
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm just thinking aloud.

01:50:49.420 --> 01:50:54.520
[Amit Varma]: But it strikes me that there might be a good sort of self selection at play here, in the

01:50:54.520 --> 01:50:59.400
[Amit Varma]: sense that the people who would have been likeliest to come into a thankless profession

01:50:59.400 --> 01:51:03.800
[Amit Varma]: like publishing in the, you know, in the 80s and 90s, and who are therefore senior in the

01:51:03.800 --> 01:51:08.840
[Amit Varma]: industry now, are people who would have been prolific readers and deeply engaged with critical

01:51:08.840 --> 01:51:16.200
[Amit Varma]: thinking and so on, and therefore are likelier to fight back against any kind of oppressive

01:51:16.200 --> 01:51:18.000
[Amit Varma]: climate coming from somewhere.

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:19.960
[Guest]: Is there perhaps something to that?

01:51:19.960 --> 01:51:25.600
[Guest]: I imagine there is because we did grow up in a time where these things were the things

01:51:25.600 --> 01:51:28.640
[Guest]: you fought for, and you continue to fight for them.

01:51:28.640 --> 01:51:34.440
[Guest]: But I also think that, in a strange way, the people who are now coming into it are coming

01:51:34.440 --> 01:51:40.520
[Guest]: into it at a time when there is an urgent need to think like this and to rethink where

01:51:40.520 --> 01:51:41.520
[Guest]: we are.

01:51:41.520 --> 01:51:47.760
[Guest]: And therefore, I'm also hopeful that the urgency we did not face, then we came to it gradually,

01:51:47.760 --> 01:51:52.920
[Guest]: they will be aware of it from the very beginning, and they will set up their goalposts and set

01:51:52.920 --> 01:51:58.640
[Guest]: up their games and boundaries already knowing that these are important turfs to guard and

01:51:58.640 --> 01:52:01.000
[Guest]: that these are important turfs to fight for.

01:52:01.000 --> 01:52:06.340
[Guest]: And as long as they also have an old guard standing by them, I think they will grow into

01:52:06.340 --> 01:52:08.960
[Guest]: people who will protect the ground for us.

01:52:08.960 --> 01:52:09.960
[Amit Varma]: That's really heartening.

01:52:09.960 --> 01:52:16.360
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on now from politics to a subject that is less worrying, which is

01:52:16.360 --> 01:52:20.240
[Amit Varma]: the nature of reading, you know, people read for different reasons, people might read for

01:52:20.240 --> 01:52:24.120
[Amit Varma]: performative reasons, they might buy a book, you know, if something wins a Booker Prize,

01:52:24.120 --> 01:52:27.960
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people who buy it, buy it because I have to have it, I feel intellectual just

01:52:27.960 --> 01:52:29.200
[Amit Varma]: by having it.

01:52:29.200 --> 01:52:33.240
[Amit Varma]: People may read for escapist reasons, which are great reasons, which is why I started

01:52:33.240 --> 01:52:39.040
[Amit Varma]: reading, for example, people might read to learn more about the world, people, I mean,

01:52:39.040 --> 01:52:42.960
[Amit Varma]: it's the best way to learn more about the world, really, and people might read to sort

01:52:42.960 --> 01:52:44.840
[Amit Varma]: of enlighten themselves and so on.

01:52:44.840 --> 01:52:48.880
[Amit Varma]: Or people might, you know, in the case, you know, as a suspicion was about many Chetan

01:52:48.880 --> 01:52:53.440
[Amit Varma]: Bhagatri, does they might read to learn the language better, which is also great.

01:52:53.440 --> 01:52:57.840
[Amit Varma]: Looking through the sort of the different kinds of reasons why people read, have those

01:52:57.840 --> 01:53:04.520
[Amit Varma]: sort of changed, you know, over the last sort of 25 years that you've been in the business?

01:53:04.520 --> 01:53:10.240
[Guest]: There's one clear difference I see in numbers, which probably tell us what people are reading.

01:53:10.240 --> 01:53:16.600
[Guest]: And that is this whole new market for the spiritual book, for the book by the gurus,

01:53:16.600 --> 01:53:24.640
[Guest]: for the book by the religious or not necessarily religious, but reformist, ashram living teachers

01:53:24.640 --> 01:53:32.560
[Guest]: of how to live and how to think and how to make yourself whatever you want to be, etc.

01:53:32.560 --> 01:53:36.040
[Guest]: Hundreds of thousands of copies are being sold of those books, and the bestseller charts

01:53:36.040 --> 01:53:38.520
[Guest]: are now ruled by them.

01:53:38.520 --> 01:53:44.040
[Guest]: Which means people are turning to the DIY in a different way from which in which they

01:53:44.040 --> 01:53:48.600
[Guest]: were turning to them earlier, which was like the Dale Geert Karnagie, how to improve how

01:53:48.600 --> 01:53:55.880
[Guest]: to you know, be better at your job sort of thing, to some kind of great need to have

01:53:55.880 --> 01:54:04.960
[Guest]: systems of peace seeking and meditation and, you know, rejigging your insides and all of

01:54:04.960 --> 01:54:06.680
[Guest]: these things that are happening.

01:54:06.680 --> 01:54:10.360
[Guest]: And the numbers show that they come from a very Hindu space.

01:54:10.360 --> 01:54:17.360
[Guest]: They come from a very mainstream space, if you want to call it that.

01:54:17.360 --> 01:54:24.780
[Guest]: And they are obviously backed by systems, by organizations.

01:54:24.780 --> 01:54:29.840
[Guest]: So there is a certain way in which they are organic and going to readers, but they're

01:54:29.840 --> 01:54:32.540
[Guest]: also institutionalized.

01:54:32.540 --> 01:54:35.920
[Guest]: So that is a new world for us.

01:54:35.920 --> 01:54:41.920
[Guest]: It's been the last few years that we've seen this market really develop into big numbers.

01:54:41.920 --> 01:54:44.720
[Guest]: For the rest of it, the categories haven't surprised us.

01:54:44.720 --> 01:54:46.960
[Guest]: I mean, they're still the same old categories.

01:54:46.960 --> 01:54:51.640
[Amit Varma]: Like I did an episode with Akshay Mukul a while back on his great book on the Gita Press.

01:54:51.640 --> 01:54:55.420
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the big revelation in that book was how much of an organized movement

01:54:55.420 --> 01:54:59.200
[Amit Varma]: that was about getting that kind of literature out there and getting people to read it and

01:54:59.200 --> 01:55:00.200
[Amit Varma]: all that.

01:55:00.200 --> 01:55:01.880
[Amit Varma]: Is this in a sense an extension of that?

01:55:01.880 --> 01:55:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Or is a lot of it just an organic quest of a lot of people now sort of having the means

01:55:08.480 --> 01:55:12.560
[Amit Varma]: and the spare time to be able to actually read books and having those same urges and

01:55:12.560 --> 01:55:14.880
[Amit Varma]: English being aspirational and growing?

01:55:14.880 --> 01:55:20.240
[Amit Varma]: Where, you know, they're sort of, I mean, I'm assuming many of these would be readers

01:55:20.240 --> 01:55:21.680
[Guest]: who don't otherwise read, right?

01:55:21.680 --> 01:55:22.680
[Guest]: Correct.

01:55:22.680 --> 01:55:27.160
[Guest]: That's why I said that in that way, they are the new category of readers who are like people

01:55:27.160 --> 01:55:30.200
[Guest]: discover Chetan Bhagat and how to read in a certain way.

01:55:30.200 --> 01:55:33.680
[Guest]: They discovered these and said, oh, I enjoy reading these books.

01:55:33.680 --> 01:55:38.000
[Guest]: I enjoy reading them in English as well, because it's not about the language.

01:55:38.000 --> 01:55:39.400
[Guest]: It's about what's being said to me.

01:55:39.400 --> 01:55:41.160
[Guest]: And I get what they're saying to me.

01:55:41.160 --> 01:55:44.840
[Guest]: So I think there are many among those people who have come to them organically in their

01:55:44.840 --> 01:55:49.720
[Guest]: own time in life, their own age or whatever it is that drives them to it.

01:55:49.720 --> 01:55:54.880
[Guest]: I also think there is an institutionalized way in which that reading is being propagated

01:55:54.880 --> 01:56:03.560
[Guest]: and nurtured, which is to do with our own society at the moment, which is to do with

01:56:03.560 --> 01:56:10.160
[Guest]: what is seen to be good to read and which prove your allegiance to a certain way of

01:56:10.160 --> 01:56:12.400
[Guest]: existence.

01:56:12.400 --> 01:56:19.040
[Guest]: And you know that this is only going to get you kudos and brownie points and not there's

01:56:19.040 --> 01:56:22.000
[Guest]: no downside to being seen to be reading this stuff.

01:56:22.000 --> 01:56:27.320
[Guest]: So I think you do fall in with the system while sometimes also finding that one book

01:56:27.320 --> 01:56:30.120
[Guest]: or two that actually makes a difference to your own life.

01:56:30.120 --> 01:56:35.560
[Amit Varma]: So are there sort of political and social implications to this in the sense that you're

01:56:35.560 --> 01:56:40.280
[Amit Varma]: not just picking up that spiritual book for, you know, your personal peace of mind or whatever,

01:56:40.280 --> 01:56:45.460
[Amit Varma]: though that might be a reason in many cases, but also out of a tribal sense of belonging

01:56:45.460 --> 01:56:49.720
[Guest]: to a community and a way of thinking and a way of living and that book reaffirms that.

01:56:49.720 --> 01:56:51.120
[Guest]: I think it does do that.

01:56:51.120 --> 01:56:55.600
[Guest]: And I think there are a lot of people out there who feel a little lost in their own

01:56:55.600 --> 01:57:00.040
[Guest]: lives, perhaps lost in not having communities around them, which is why they seek out others

01:57:00.040 --> 01:57:01.460
[Guest]: to belong to.

01:57:01.460 --> 01:57:06.080
[Guest]: And when they do, then these texts and these readings and remember, I would not underestimate

01:57:06.080 --> 01:57:10.560
[Guest]: the WhatsApp universes we occupy now, because there's a lot of little wisdoms and little

01:57:10.560 --> 01:57:15.000
[Guest]: videos that do the rounds that somebody said something which made a lot of sense to you.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:18.000
[Guest]: And then you say, oh, and you go into the bookshop, or you browsing online, and you

01:57:18.000 --> 01:57:20.240
[Guest]: suddenly see a whole book by that person.

01:57:20.240 --> 01:57:23.360
[Guest]: And you say, I'm sure there's something there for me and you buy it and you may not read

01:57:23.360 --> 01:57:24.840
[Guest]: it cover to cover.

01:57:24.840 --> 01:57:27.680
[Guest]: But there will be little nuggets, there will be little things in it, which you will apply

01:57:27.680 --> 01:57:29.000
[Guest]: to yourself.

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:34.440
[Guest]: So you will then next time buy another one by somebody else, maybe in that same category,

01:57:34.440 --> 01:57:38.080
[Guest]: because it gives you something which is a learning which is something that you want

01:57:38.080 --> 01:57:43.320
[Guest]: for yourself in this really vital way, which you may not have felt at another time in your

01:57:43.320 --> 01:57:45.120
[Amit Varma]: life, but you certainly do now.

01:57:45.120 --> 01:57:48.480
[Amit Varma]: And if there's something there that you know, is part of your value system, buying it is

01:57:48.480 --> 01:57:53.200
[Amit Varma]: like an affirmation of who you are, in a sense, this is who I am, this is where I kind of

01:57:53.200 --> 01:57:54.200
[Amit Varma]: belong.

01:57:54.200 --> 01:57:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk a little bit about ebooks, you know, when the Kindle first came about, I

01:57:57.600 --> 01:58:03.120
[Amit Varma]: mean, I was just an evangelist, because for me, books were the words that an author writes,

01:58:03.120 --> 01:58:04.880
[Amit Varma]: yeah, you know, the rest is packaging.

01:58:04.880 --> 01:58:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And I also, you know, being of the age I am do feel nostalgic for the particular packaging

01:58:09.120 --> 01:58:10.120
[Amit Varma]: in which we read our books.

01:58:10.120 --> 01:58:13.960
[Amit Varma]: But at the end of the day, it's wood pulp, it's paper, it's just packaging and the words

01:58:13.960 --> 01:58:15.760
[Amit Varma]: are everything.

01:58:15.760 --> 01:58:20.160
[Amit Varma]: And I imagine rather naively that after my generation dies out, all the kids will just

01:58:20.160 --> 01:58:22.040
[Amit Varma]: be reading ebooks, right?

01:58:22.040 --> 01:58:23.600
[Amit Varma]: And that's not that's clearly not happened.

01:58:23.600 --> 01:58:26.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, physical books are selling more than ever.

01:58:26.480 --> 01:58:27.480
[Unknown]: Is this something you foresaw?

01:58:27.480 --> 01:58:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Or you know, why do you think this is?

01:58:29.880 --> 01:58:34.080
[Guest]: I think that in the beginning, everyone in India also thought we'd follow the path of

01:58:34.080 --> 01:58:35.240
[Guest]: the West.

01:58:35.240 --> 01:58:39.320
[Guest]: And in the US, for instance, they were looking at something like 50% of the market being

01:58:39.320 --> 01:58:41.600
[Guest]: ebooks and 50% physical books.

01:58:41.600 --> 01:58:44.960
[Guest]: I think this was around 2011 when ebooks outsold, but then it flipped back.

01:58:44.960 --> 01:58:47.440
[Guest]: Then it started to yeah, then it started to climb back.

01:58:47.440 --> 01:58:50.720
[Guest]: And while we were pitching ahead, so I remember when you made your five year plans, you'd

01:58:50.720 --> 01:58:55.120
[Guest]: say five years from now, you would have like 50% ebooks and 50% physical, etc.

01:58:55.120 --> 01:58:58.760
[Guest]: And you thought you were planning technology towards that, etc.

01:58:58.760 --> 01:59:00.340
[Guest]: And suddenly, it changed.

01:59:00.340 --> 01:59:05.440
[Guest]: And you started to see that 50% going back to 40 to 30 to whatever it is now maybe 25

01:59:05.440 --> 01:59:06.960
[Guest]: or 35.

01:59:06.960 --> 01:59:10.800
[Guest]: And you realize that that is something that you're not going to reach the 50% before going

01:59:10.800 --> 01:59:11.800
[Guest]: back to 25.

01:59:11.800 --> 01:59:16.520
[Guest]: You're probably going to climb gradually up to like 25 20% at the most, and stay there

01:59:16.520 --> 01:59:18.640
[Guest]: is the feeling we have now.

01:59:18.640 --> 01:59:26.080
[Guest]: And there is in India for sure, every publisher is still banking on selling physical books.

01:59:26.080 --> 01:59:29.280
[Guest]: There's a little bit of an exception once in a while.

01:59:29.280 --> 01:59:31.000
[Guest]: I mean, there are certain kinds of categories.

01:59:31.000 --> 01:59:35.480
[Guest]: For instance, I remember when Abdul Kalam's books first came out, and ebooks were starting

01:59:35.480 --> 01:59:36.480
[Guest]: to be popular.

01:59:36.480 --> 01:59:41.000
[Guest]: There were a lot of people who wanted to read his books outside of India as well.

01:59:41.000 --> 01:59:42.880
[Guest]: And for them, the ebook was easier.

01:59:42.880 --> 01:59:47.240
[Guest]: So you had some books and I remember this Marathi publisher telling me that the Marathi

01:59:47.240 --> 01:59:52.720
[Guest]: reading diaspora were buying a lot of ebooks of the big novels in Marathi.

01:59:52.720 --> 01:59:56.960
[Guest]: So there were pockets where you saw that this could be the future.

01:59:56.960 --> 02:00:03.000
[Guest]: But each time then the numbers came down to okay, 5%, 7%, 10%, whatever.

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:06.440
[Guest]: And it never really became a challenge to the physical book.

02:00:06.440 --> 02:00:08.080
[Guest]: And I think that's where we are at now.

02:00:08.080 --> 02:00:12.800
[Guest]: We're not even anticipating a future at the moment where the ebook will take over.

02:00:12.800 --> 02:00:16.240
[Amit Varma]: And give me a sense, I mean, perhaps I should have asked this question right at the start.

02:00:16.240 --> 02:00:21.040
[Amit Varma]: But give me a sense of how readership has evolved in India through the years that you've

02:00:21.040 --> 02:00:23.880
[Amit Varma]: been part of the publishing industry just in terms of numbers.

02:00:23.880 --> 02:00:25.560
[Amit Varma]: Like do more people read now?

02:00:25.560 --> 02:00:26.800
[Amit Varma]: Do more books get sold?

02:00:26.800 --> 02:00:27.840
[Amit Varma]: Have there been booms?

02:00:27.840 --> 02:00:30.840
[Amit Varma]: Have there been sort of crisis?

02:00:30.840 --> 02:00:34.280
[Guest]: I think books every year, we do sell more books than the previous year.

02:00:34.280 --> 02:00:35.280
[Guest]: There's no doubt about that.

02:00:35.280 --> 02:00:37.120
[Guest]: The children's market has been growing steadily.

02:00:37.120 --> 02:00:41.560
[Guest]: There are years, I mean, several years where retailers have said they have grown by like

02:00:41.560 --> 02:00:43.800
[Guest]: 25% over the previous year.

02:00:43.800 --> 02:00:46.240
[Guest]: So that is obviously you can see why.

02:00:46.240 --> 02:00:50.480
[Guest]: I mean, there are more children coming in through the language systems into English.

02:00:50.480 --> 02:00:52.240
[Amit Varma]: That's our only demographic dividend.

02:00:52.240 --> 02:00:54.240
[Guest]: Yes, there's no doubt about that.

02:00:54.240 --> 02:00:56.760
[Guest]: So that is definitely a growth.

02:00:56.760 --> 02:01:01.480
[Guest]: Educational publishing, school books grow by sometimes 100%, 50%, 100% depending on

02:01:01.480 --> 02:01:03.480
[Guest]: the company you're in.

02:01:03.480 --> 02:01:04.760
[Guest]: That is also explicable.

02:01:04.760 --> 02:01:06.760
[Guest]: You know how many more students are joining schools?

02:01:06.760 --> 02:01:09.200
[Guest]: How many more schools are starting up, etc.

02:01:09.200 --> 02:01:15.000
[Guest]: But in the choice space where you are actually choosing to read a book because you want to

02:01:15.000 --> 02:01:21.360
[Guest]: spend time with it and not for any compulsion, I think even that space has been growing.

02:01:21.360 --> 02:01:24.360
[Guest]: As I said, sometimes in this category, sometimes in that.

02:01:24.360 --> 02:01:32.680
[Guest]: But if you look at the overall picture, the bestseller has gone from being 5,000 or 10,000

02:01:32.680 --> 02:01:40.320
[Guest]: to 100,000 or 50,000 copies, which in itself is a marker of how much more we expect our

02:01:40.320 --> 02:01:41.640
[Guest]: better books to do.

02:01:41.640 --> 02:01:45.880
[Guest]: So while your average book, as I said, may still be 2,000 to 3,000 copies, when you say

02:01:45.880 --> 02:01:50.280
[Guest]: something is doing well, you do not mean 3,000 or 4,000 anymore.

02:01:50.280 --> 02:01:53.760
[Guest]: When you say a book is doing well, you're actually saying where at least 10,000 copies

02:01:53.760 --> 02:01:56.800
[Guest]: have sold and not at a really cheap price.

02:01:56.800 --> 02:02:01.120
[Guest]: Maybe I'm not when you're talking about a book that is a mass market novel, for instance,

02:02:01.120 --> 02:02:06.120
[Guest]: which is like a 200 rupee book or a 250 book, then you're not even going to look at 10,000

02:02:06.120 --> 02:02:07.240
[Guest]: copies as a bestseller.

02:02:07.240 --> 02:02:10.440
[Guest]: Then you're only going to talk about it as a bestseller when it's reached like a 50,000

02:02:10.440 --> 02:02:11.440
[Guest]: or something.

02:02:11.440 --> 02:02:12.440
[Guest]: Right.

02:02:12.440 --> 02:02:14.800
[Guest]: So in that sense, yes, everything is growing.

02:02:14.800 --> 02:02:17.520
[Guest]: Everything is looking better year after year.

02:02:17.520 --> 02:02:21.060
[Guest]: Most publishing houses are able to grow to some percentage or the other every year.

02:02:21.060 --> 02:02:26.120
[Guest]: It's not static like it is in several Western publishing houses.

02:02:26.120 --> 02:02:32.360
[Guest]: The question is only, are we growing in the right segments according to ourselves?

02:02:32.360 --> 02:02:36.800
[Guest]: Are we at the right books or the books that we think deserve to be selling more?

02:02:36.800 --> 02:02:38.420
[Guest]: Are they selling more?

02:02:38.420 --> 02:02:43.240
[Guest]: Are we getting the best writers the space that they should get as opposed to books that

02:02:43.240 --> 02:02:49.040
[Guest]: are just being churned out and read and republished or whatever without enough care to them?

02:02:49.040 --> 02:02:51.720
[Guest]: So those are questions that I think will always exist.

02:02:51.720 --> 02:02:55.620
[Guest]: I mean, there'll always be filters that some want to apply and there'll always be gateways

02:02:55.620 --> 02:02:57.920
[Guest]: that other people want to break open.

02:02:57.920 --> 02:02:59.760
[Guest]: But that I think all of it coexists.

02:02:59.760 --> 02:03:04.340
[Guest]: There will be some in this segment and some in that and together they will grow.

02:03:04.340 --> 02:03:06.920
[Guest]: But you can't knock out one for another.

02:03:06.920 --> 02:03:11.040
[Amit Varma]: And speaking of filters, how has discovery changed over these last 25 years?

02:03:11.040 --> 02:03:15.440
[Amit Varma]: Like back in the day, you know, your discovery, I imagine, would be one of three ways you

02:03:15.440 --> 02:03:19.040
[Amit Varma]: read about a book in the newspaper, maybe through a news review and a book review, and

02:03:19.040 --> 02:03:20.400
[Amit Varma]: there weren't many of those.

02:03:20.400 --> 02:03:25.520
[Amit Varma]: You'd hear about it by word of mouth, or you'd see it in the display of your local bookstore.

02:03:25.520 --> 02:03:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Well, now I think that ways of discovery must surely be so much more disparate.

02:03:30.240 --> 02:03:34.200
[Amit Varma]: And especially in Bombay, I hardly get to go to a bookstore anymore.

02:03:34.200 --> 02:03:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And when I do, I'm usually not buying very much.

02:03:37.360 --> 02:03:41.920
[Unknown]: I'm ashamed to say I'm just looking in my Amazon and, you know, making lists of books

02:03:41.920 --> 02:03:46.680
[Amit Varma]: that I want to acquire in whatever form.

02:03:46.680 --> 02:03:48.120
[Amit Varma]: How has the discovery changed?

02:03:48.120 --> 02:03:54.440
[Amit Varma]: And following on from that, how does a publisher then cater their marketing to how people discover

02:03:54.440 --> 02:03:55.440
[Amit Varma]: books?

02:03:55.440 --> 02:03:57.400
[Amit Varma]: Is social media really a big part of that?

02:03:57.400 --> 02:04:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Do you then find yourself chasing influencers and getting them to write books, simply because

02:04:02.200 --> 02:04:06.200
[Amit Varma]: they are influencers, which I imagine would be a wrong reason, but from one point of view

02:04:06.200 --> 02:04:08.120
[Guest]: might make sense.

02:04:08.120 --> 02:04:09.120
[Guest]: I think it has changed.

02:04:09.120 --> 02:04:14.160
[Guest]: I mean, of course, there's the usual old ways, friends recommended, universities recommended,

02:04:14.160 --> 02:04:18.000
[Guest]: or you find it in a bookstore, etc.

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:24.720
[Guest]: But a lot of people now are finding that they're browsing online and coming up with a book

02:04:24.720 --> 02:04:27.720
[Guest]: that they then chase down to see the reviews.

02:04:27.720 --> 02:04:35.760
[Guest]: And Amazon five star reviews by 300 people will drive you to buy a book in a way that

02:04:35.760 --> 02:04:38.560
[Guest]: I think you would have not thought possible earlier.

02:04:38.560 --> 02:04:44.320
[Guest]: Because there was still that sense that the reviewer who's a professional reviewer, who

02:04:44.320 --> 02:04:51.360
[Guest]: writes for it in a sanctified space like a newspaper, has a view that is more to be respected

02:04:51.360 --> 02:04:55.400
[Guest]: and to be followed up on by purchase of the book.

02:04:55.400 --> 02:04:59.560
[Guest]: But now people are saying, I actually I don't care who said it.

02:04:59.560 --> 02:05:04.400
[Guest]: I trust these hundred people on because those are like they have no stake in anything.

02:05:04.400 --> 02:05:09.240
[Guest]: I believe that they're speaking what they want to say and what they actually believe.

02:05:09.240 --> 02:05:10.760
[Guest]: And I'm willing to go by that.

02:05:10.760 --> 02:05:16.480
[Guest]: So a lot of people will buy a book after reading online reviews, which is a whole new thing,

02:05:16.480 --> 02:05:20.960
[Guest]: which means that your marketing, as you said, has to be geared towards online discovery.

02:05:20.960 --> 02:05:25.980
[Guest]: It can't just be POS in stores, can't be visibility in bookshops alone.

02:05:25.980 --> 02:05:30.880
[Guest]: It really needs people to look at a post by someone and follow the link to buy the book

02:05:30.880 --> 02:05:34.080
[Guest]: right then and there because it's a possible.

02:05:34.080 --> 02:05:38.960
[Guest]: And when an influencer like say Ashashi Tharoor says, I don't remember the last time he said

02:05:38.960 --> 02:05:45.080
[Guest]: this, but when he does say, I loved this book and puts up something by the author, I am

02:05:45.080 --> 02:05:49.280
[Guest]: absolutely sure that a lot of people would follow that and go buy the book immediately.

02:05:49.280 --> 02:05:54.880
[Guest]: We see spikes when an influencer who's like a major influencer says something positive

02:05:54.880 --> 02:05:56.960
[Guest]: about a book on Insta or Twitter.

02:05:56.960 --> 02:05:59.580
[Guest]: We see that people go online and buy the book.

02:05:59.580 --> 02:06:05.060
[Guest]: We don't see that spike so much in the stores, but we see it as an almost instinctive response

02:06:05.060 --> 02:06:08.960
[Guest]: that oh, then I want it and I am able to buy it immediately online.

02:06:08.960 --> 02:06:10.320
[Guest]: So I will do that.

02:06:10.320 --> 02:06:15.580
[Guest]: So we do invest a lot more time and money and effort in getting our social media right,

02:06:15.580 --> 02:06:19.280
[Guest]: in following the right people on Insta and Twitter and Facebook to get that.

02:06:19.280 --> 02:06:23.160
[Guest]: A lot more Facebook live chats happen when you're launching a book.

02:06:23.160 --> 02:06:27.000
[Guest]: Twitter Blueroom is used to have conversations with writers.

02:06:27.000 --> 02:06:33.160
[Guest]: So there is that sense that the real committed reader who goes to a bookshop, who actually

02:06:33.160 --> 02:06:37.520
[Guest]: makes the effort to go to a bookshop, will discover the books that they need to discover.

02:06:37.520 --> 02:06:41.700
[Guest]: We don't need to worry about them so much, but it's the others that you want to get,

02:06:41.700 --> 02:06:48.840
[Guest]: the ones who are not committed, who could choose to read or not read and would be completely

02:06:48.840 --> 02:06:53.840
[Guest]: almost licentious in their, you know, they can read something from the US or the UK or

02:06:53.840 --> 02:06:56.240
[Guest]: India or Europe or whatever.

02:06:56.240 --> 02:06:59.360
[Guest]: How do you get them to focus on the book that you want them to read?

02:06:59.360 --> 02:07:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Who will read something and love it and say, wow, I didn't know I needed this.

02:07:02.760 --> 02:07:03.760
[Guest]: Exactly.

02:07:03.760 --> 02:07:06.920
[Guest]: And once they say that to five more people, and once five more people read it and put

02:07:06.920 --> 02:07:11.400
[Guest]: up great reviews, and then five other people protest that and there's a little bit of an

02:07:11.400 --> 02:07:15.720
[Guest]: environment of, you know, we are reading and actually engaging with this book, then it

02:07:15.720 --> 02:07:16.720
[Guest]: will take off differently.

02:07:16.720 --> 02:07:21.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, I think back on how I used to sort of read books once upon a time that let's

02:07:21.800 --> 02:07:25.480
[Amit Varma]: say I'm taking a local train from Andheri to Churchgate 20 years ago, and I'll carry

02:07:25.480 --> 02:07:27.120
[Amit Varma]: a book with me.

02:07:27.120 --> 02:07:30.680
[Amit Varma]: And today, if I'm on a commute that long, I'll be looking at my smartphone and I'll

02:07:30.680 --> 02:07:35.600
[Amit Varma]: be on Twitter, or I'll be listening to a podcast, perhaps, which is not necessarily a bad thing.

02:07:35.600 --> 02:07:39.480
[Amit Varma]: And doing things like that, or when I go to bed at night, you know, I'll have a little

02:07:39.480 --> 02:07:43.400
[Amit Varma]: bit of bedside reading going on. And now most people are essentially turning off their blue

02:07:43.400 --> 02:07:47.680
[Amit Varma]: screens and hopefully, you know, in some cases reading the Kindle on their phone, but that's

02:07:47.680 --> 02:07:48.680
[Amit Varma]: less and less likely.

02:07:48.680 --> 02:07:52.360
[Amit Varma]: So I'll sort of I've taken up a lot of your time, I'll end this episode by asking you

02:07:52.360 --> 02:07:56.840
[Amit Varma]: a question I ask all my guests about whatever subject we're talking about, that looking

02:07:56.840 --> 02:08:02.440
[Amit Varma]: at publishing specifically and reading in general over the next 10 to 20 years, what

02:08:02.440 --> 02:08:05.200
[Amit Varma]: gives you hope and what gives you despair?

02:08:05.200 --> 02:08:12.720
[Guest]: What gives me despair is the people I see around me, including my children, who do not

02:08:12.720 --> 02:08:18.760
[Guest]: think books are the mainstay of their lives and would think books are perfectly dispensable.

02:08:18.760 --> 02:08:25.760
[Guest]: And that what they get from YouTube, or from whatever else they're engaged on in on the

02:08:25.760 --> 02:08:33.280
[Guest]: smart screen is absolutely good enough for them.

02:08:33.280 --> 02:08:37.760
[Guest]: I don't know how long those things last, whether they are phases, and maybe they will change.

02:08:37.760 --> 02:08:41.280
[Amit Varma]: Maybe they secretly read every day. This is just a posturing for you. They're rebelling

02:08:41.280 --> 02:08:42.280
[Amit Varma]: against their mother.

02:08:42.280 --> 02:08:47.960
[Guest]: Possible. But I mean, they're just reflective of a whole community of people out there who

02:08:47.960 --> 02:08:53.080
[Guest]: I think read less than I would like them to. But you know, the thing is, when I was growing

02:08:53.080 --> 02:08:58.960
[Guest]: up, or you were growing up possibly, or other people our age were, I don't think our mothers

02:08:58.960 --> 02:09:04.040
[Guest]: or fathers read stories to us. I think they told us stories when we went to bed. But somewhere

02:09:04.040 --> 02:09:10.960
[Guest]: along the way, we decided that reading a book to a child was like the best way to educate

02:09:10.960 --> 02:09:16.440
[Guest]: them and bring them up to date with, you know, life and times of the world and their characters.

02:09:16.440 --> 02:09:21.840
[Guest]: And then when we saw that they were reading less, we decided that, oh, my God, we have

02:09:21.840 --> 02:09:27.820
[Guest]: completely transformed and the society is no longer reading. But when were they reading?

02:09:27.820 --> 02:09:32.280
[Guest]: We tend to think everything in our life is the standard by which everything else has

02:09:32.280 --> 02:09:38.600
[Guest]: to be measured. And that's partly why we think reading is so important. But if you look at

02:09:38.600 --> 02:09:45.080
[Guest]: it another way, as long as the stories continue, as long as people will use narrative in their

02:09:45.080 --> 02:09:51.120
[Guest]: own ways, whatever those ways are, and they will continue to get people to think through

02:09:51.120 --> 02:09:58.200
[Guest]: those stories, bedtime or in school, or just the way we talk to each other, I think that's

02:09:58.200 --> 02:10:04.240
[Guest]: good enough. I think its form is only so important. Whether it's a printed book, whether it's

02:10:04.240 --> 02:10:11.240
[Guest]: on screen, whether it's written or told or watched. I think the story is the heart of

02:10:11.240 --> 02:10:17.460
[Guest]: the matter. And that's what gives me hope that as long as the story is required for

02:10:17.460 --> 02:10:22.240
[Guest]: us and as long as we love the story, we will continue to find new ways and more interesting

02:10:22.240 --> 02:10:32.800
[Guest]: ways to tell that story. And a book is one part of that. And I think we should stop prioritizing

02:10:32.800 --> 02:10:41.780
[Guest]: form over content. And as we change, as lives change around us, people will find different

02:10:41.780 --> 02:10:48.480
[Guest]: ways of packaging the story. But I don't think the story is going away. And that's what gives

02:10:48.480 --> 02:10:49.480
[Guest]: me hope.

02:10:49.480 --> 02:10:53.000
[Amit Varma]: These are very wise words. I agree with you entirely. And I would add to that by saying

02:10:53.000 --> 02:10:57.120
[Amit Varma]: that it's okay if you don't read as much as your parents think you should as long as you

02:10:57.120 --> 02:11:01.560
